[[Paul Buckle]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Sean Canham]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Steve Collis]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Matt Villis]]\n{{col-break}}\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Chris Curran (footballer born September 1971)|Chris Curran]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Steve Flack]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Ben Foster (footballer)|Ben Foster]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[George Friend]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Matthew Hewlett]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Scott Hiley]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Kevin Hill (footballer)|Kevin Hill]]\n*{{flagicon|WAL}}[[Chris Holloway]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Chris Vinnicombe]]\n{{col-break}}\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Ian Hutchinson (footballer born 1972)|Ian Hutchinson]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[John Impey]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Scott Laird]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Ryan Leonard]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Sam Malsom]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Nicky Marker]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Barry McConnell]]\n*{{flagicon|WAL}}[[Kurt Nogan]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Phil Walsh (English footballer)|Phil Walsh]]\n{{col-break}}\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Mark Ovendale]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Richard Pears]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Graeme Power (footballer, born 1977)|Graeme Power]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Stephen Reed (footballer)|Stephen Reed]]\n*{{flagicon|WAL}}[[Jason Rees (footballer)|Jason Rees]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}Nathan Rudge\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Mark Saunders (footballer)|Mark Saunders]]\n*{{flagicon|ENG}}[[Danny Seaborne]]\n*{{flagicon|SIN}}[[John Wilkinson (Singaporean footballer)|John Wilkinson]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n*A list of Tiverton Players former and current can be found, including those that do not meet the criteria above here:[[:Category:Tiverton Town F.C. players]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100126021821/http://www.tivertontownfc.com/ Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060504200027/http://www.tivertontownyouth.co.uk/ Youth Development & Academy]\n*{{fchd|id=TIVERTOT|name=Tiverton Town}}\n*[http://www.tivvyarchive.co.uk/ Tivvy Archive]\n*[https://twitter.com/tivertontownfc Official Twitter Page]\n\n{{Southern League}}\n{{coord|50|54|33.29|N|3|29|24.60|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Southern Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1913]]\n[[Category:Tiverton, Devon]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Devon]]\n[[Category:1913 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Tiverton Town\n| image    = TivertonTown.png\n| image_size  = 200px\n| fullname = Tiverton Town Football Club\n| nickname = ''\"Tivvy\"'' ''\"Yellows\"'' The Gold Army\n| founded  = 1913 (as Tiverton Athletic)\n| ground   = Ladysmead, [[Tiverton, Devon|Tiverton]]\n| capacity = 3,500 (520 seated)\n| chairman = Peter Buxton\n| manager  = [[Martyn Rogers]]\n| league   = {{English football updater|TivertoT}}\n| season   = {{English football updater|TivertoT2}}\n| position = {{English football updater|TivertoT3}}\n| website  = http://www.tivertontownfc.co.uk/\n|  pattern_la1=_yellowlower|pattern_b1=_blackcollar|pattern_ra1=_yellowlower|pattern_so1=_blacktop\n|  leftarm1=000000|body1=FFFF00|rightarm1=000000|shorts1=FFFF00|socks1=FFFF00\n|  pattern_la2= |pattern_b2= |pattern_ra2=|pattern_so2=_blacktop\n|  leftarm2=FFFFFF|body2=FFFFFF|rightarm2=FFFFFF|shorts2=FFFFFF|socks2=FFFFFF\n}}\n\n'''Tiverton Town Football Club''' are an English [[association football|football]] club based in [[Tiverton, Devon|Tiverton]], Devon. The club are currently members of the {{English football updater|TivertoT}} and play at Ladysmead.\n\n==History==\nThe club was established in 1913 as '''Tiverton Athletic''', and initially played at the Athletic Ground. They joined the East Devon League, winning the Senior Division in 1924\u201325, 1925\u201326, 1926\u201327 and 1927\u201328. They then joined the [[North Devon Football League|North Devon League]], winning it in 1931\u201332, after which they transferred to the Exeter & District League, which they won in 1933\u201334.\n\nIn 1951\u201352 the club won the league's Senior Division, and in 1956 won the [[Devon Senior Cup]] for the first time. They won the league again in 1964\u201365 and 1965\u201366, a season in which they also won the Senior Cup for a second time.\n\nIn 1973 the club joined the [[Western Football League|Western League]]. They were relegated to Division One at the end of the 1980\u201381 season after finishing bottom of the league. After finishing as runners-up in 1988\u201389, they were promoted back to the Premier Division. Following two fourth-placed finishes, the club finished third in 1991\u201392, second in 1992\u201393 (a season in which they also won the League Cup for the first time), and won the league and League Cup double in 1993\u201394. They won the league again the following season, and after finishing as runners-up in 1995\u201396, a season in which they also picked up the League Cup, achieved back-to-back titles again in 1996\u201397 (a double season) and 1997\u201398. They also won the FA Vase in 1998, beating [[Tow Law Town F.C.|Tow Law Town]] 1\u20130 in the final.\n\nIn 1998\u201399 the club won the [[FA Vase]] again, beating [[Bedlington Terriers F.C.|Bedlington Terriers]] 1\u20130, and finished second in the league, earning promotion to Division One West of the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]]. In [[2000\u201301 Southern Football League|2000\u201301]] they finished second, and were promoted to the Premier Division, where they remained until 2011. In [[2006\u201307 Southern Football League|2006\u201307]] they won the Southern League Cup.\n\nOn 18 April 2012 it was announced in the national press that Tiverton had appointed 27-year-old internet entrepreneur Matthew Conridge as their new chairman. Believed to be one of the youngest football chairman in the UK ever Conridge was quoted as saying, ''\"I'm not here to chuck thousands of pounds into a black hole, I'm here to pull everyone together and work with a good team......This club will not spend more than it can afford to chase a dream......If we can't afford a budget to go to Blue Square Bet South we won't pay it\".''<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17753683 BBC report on the appointment]</ref>\n\nOn 30 April 2013 Tiverton Town released a press release as follows \"Tiverton Town can confirm that Matthew Conridge has stepped down as Chairman of Tiverton Town to pursue other business interests. The club would like to place on record its gratitude for all his hard work whilst in the position. Former Tivvy chairman Dave Wright is taking over the position of chairman for the time being. The club also wishes to confirm the departure of interim manager Jamie Ward together with his assistant Paul Short.\"{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nIn May 2013 Tiverton town released the following press release to announce the arrival of John Clarkson as their new manager \"John Clarkson was tonight introduced to the media and Tivvy fans at a press conference at Ladysmead. Clarkson has arrived from Spain where he was manager of [[Ontinyent CF|Ontinyent]] in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|Segunda B]]. He had been managing in Spain for the last six years\".\n\nIn May 2014, Tiverton Town manager John Clarkson stepped down from the position following the teams disappointing 2\u20130 Devon Bowl Final defeat to Plymouth Parkway who were playing in the league below Tiverton. He had led the side to the play-off's, where they lost to 9-man Paulton, and two Cup finals but cited the last couple of months as the reason he was going, \"The last couple of months have really taken it out of me, three or four games a week was just too much\" He added,\"I'm off to take my coaching badges during the summer and once I've completed them I will decide on what I'm going to do\"\nDespite a much higher wage budget than other teams in the league (due to John Clarkson's financial input) the club could not reach its aim of promotion in its centenary season.\nAt the end of the season many of the club's higher profile players left following John Clarkson's resignation and the reduction of the wage budget.\nYellows legend [[Martyn Rogers]] was named as Clarkson's replacement and given the task of rebuilding the squad on a much more restricted wage budget.\n\nIn the 2016/17 season Tiverton Town gained promotion to the Southern League Premier Division. They beat Salisbury 0\u20132 with goals from Michael Landricombe and Tom Bath in the playoff final in front of over 2,000, returning them to the Southern League Premier after being relegated in 2011.\n\nIn the 2017/18 season following promotion from the 8th teir Tivvy finished in a highly respectable position of 6th. Especially considering the low budget and crowds compared to the top 5 and most of the league. However despite this Tivvy managed to beat 4 of the top 5 with playoff hopes ending due to poor away form.\n\n==Stadium==\nThe club currently play at The Ian Moorcroft Stadium, Ladysmead, Bolham Road, Tiverton, Devon, EX16 6SG.\n\nOpened in 1946, the ground has a capacity of 3,500, of which 520 is seated.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pyramidpassion.co.uk/html/tiverton_town.html|title=Tiverton Town ground guide|publisher=Pyramid Passion|accessdate=11 November 2007}}</ref>\n\nAs Tiverton Athletic, the club played its home games at the Athletic Ground, now known as Amory Park. The ground boasted a huge wooden pavilion with a seated veranda, which was quite extravagant for a non-league club in the 1910s. In 1921, Athletic were effectively evicted from their ground and moved to a local rugby pitch, Elm Field (aka \"The Elms\"), with the reformed rugby club taking their place at their old ground. The Elms housed a wooden 150-seat stand on one side, with grass banks behind the goals being the only other spectator zones.\n\nThe Elms was virtually destroyed during [[World War II]], meaning the club had to move, eventually relocating to Ladysmead. The club's record attendance of 3,000 came in the [[1994\u201395 FA Cup|FA Cup]] first round, against [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] on 12 November 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tiverton Town FC|url=http://www.tivertontownfc.com/club/history/general/|publisher=Tiverton Town FC|accessdate=6 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309162245/http://www.tivertontownfc.com/club/history/general/|archivedate=9 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Players==\n:''As of 15 July 2019.''<ref name=\"Tiverton Town FC Player Profiles\">{{cite news\n |title        = Tiverton Town FC Player Profiles\n |url          = http://www.tivertontownfc.com/1st-team-squad\n |publisher    = Tiverton Town Official Website\n |date         = 14 June 2017\n |accessdate   = 14 June 2017\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170609075644/http://www.tivertontownfc.com/1st-team-squad/\n |archive-date = 15 July 2019\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n===Current squad===\n\n{{fs start}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=GK|name=Lewis Williams}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=Jordan Dyer}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=Pierce Mitchell}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=Noah Smerdon}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Jordan Bentley]]}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=Michael Landricombe}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=George Rogers}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Michael Peck (footballer)|Michael Peck]]}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[River Allen (footballer)|River Allen]]}} [[Captain (association football)|(captain)]]\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Chris Shephard]]}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=Scott Rogers}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=Steve Colwell}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=Jordan Bastin}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=George Nancekivell}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Joshua Key (footballer)|Joshua Key]]}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=MF|n