{"title_page": "Pe\u0111a Grbin", "text_new": "{{short description|Croatian lawyer and politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name               = Pe\u0111a Grbin\n|image              = Pedja_Grbin.jpg\n|imagesize          = \n|caption            = \n|office             = [[Member of Parliament (Croatia)|Member of Parliament]]\n|term_start         = 22 December 2011\n|term_end           = \n|constituency       = VIII electoral district\n|office2            = Chairman of the Judiciary Committee of the Croatian Parliament\n|term_start2        = 28 February 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabor.hr/en/members-parliament/grbin-peda-9-term |title=Hrvatski sabor |website=Sabor.hr |date= |accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|term_end2          =  \n|predecessor2       = [[Orsat Miljeni\u0107]]\n|successor2         = \n|office3            = Chairman of the Committee on the Constitution, Standing Orders and Political System of the Croatian Parliament\n|term_start3        = 12 October 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabor.hr/Default.aspx?art=50408 |title=Hrvatski sabor |website=Sabor.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-05-08}}</ref>\n|term_end3          = 28 December 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabor.hr/izbor-predsjednika-potpredsjednika-i-clanova-manda |title=Hrvatski sabor |website=Sabor.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-05-08}}</ref> \n|predecessor3       = [[Josip Leko]]\n|successor3         = [[Robert Podolnjak]]\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1979|05|24|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = [[Pula]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]]<br />{{small|(now [[Croatia]])}}\n|death_date         = \n|death_place        = \n|restingplace       = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|nationality        = [[Croatia]]n\n|party              = [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] (1998\u2013present)\n|spouse             = \n|children           = \n|alma_mater         = [[University of Zagreb]]\n|profession         = Lawyer\n|occupation         = Politician\n}}\n\n'''Pe\u0111a Grbin''' (born 24 May 1979) is a [[Croatia]]n lawyer and politician who represents [[Croatian Parliament electoral districts|VIII electoral district]] in the [[Croatian Parliament]] since 2011. He served as the Chairman of the Parliament's Committee on the Constitution, Standing Orders and Political System from 2012 until 2015.<ref name=\"Biography\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.sabor.hr/Default.aspx?sec=6260 |website=Sabor.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-05-08\n| language = English\n| title = Biography at the official web page of the Croatian Parliament\n}}</ref> He was vice president of the centre-left [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] (SDP) from 2016 to 2018 when he was suspended from that position.<ref name= \"Biography at www.biografija.com\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.biografija.com/peda-grbin/ |website=www.biografija.com |date= |accessdate=2017-11-17\n| language = Croatian\n| title = Pe\u0111a Grbin biografija}}</ref><ref name= total-croatia-news>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.total-croatia-news.com/politics/29783-sdp-suspends-senior-officials |website=www.total-croatia-news.com |date= |accessdate=2018-11-16\n| language = English\n| title = SDP Suspends Senior Officials}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and professional career==\nGrbin attended elementary and high school in [[Pula]], after which he enrolled in the [[Faculty of Law, University of Zagreb|Zagreb Faculty of Law]] from which he graduated in 2003. During elementary and high school days he played basketball for the local basketball team ''Gradine Pula''. After graduating, Grbin worked as a trainee in a law office and afterwards as an attorney from 2006 to 2011.<ref name= tportal>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/izbori2013/264633/Kako-SDP-ov-Veli-Joza-planira-poraziti-jakog-Miletica.html |website=tportal.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-05-08\n| language = Croatian\n| title = Kako SDP-ov Veli Jo\u017ee planira poraziti jakog Mileti\u0107a\n}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nAfter serving as a city councilor and a member of the municipal executive council in Pula, Grbin successfully ran in [[2011 Croatian parliamentary election|2011 parliamentary election]], and was elected to the Parliament in the VIII electoral district. He was reelected in [[2015 Croatian parliamentary election|2015]].<ref name= tportal />\n\n===Early career===\n\nGrbin joined SDP in 1998, and soon after that entered [[SDP Youth Forum]] where he was secretary general from 2001 to 2002. After graduating from law school he returned to Pula where he served first as a member of the municipal executive council from 2005 to 2009 and than as a city councilor from 2009 to 2013. Grbin was elected to the head committee of SDP in 2004 and has been a member of that party governing body until 2016 when he was elected to the party presidency.<ref name= sdp_izbori>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.sdp.hr/aktualno/izabrane-nove-clanice-clanovi-organa-sdp-a/ |website=sdp.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-05-08\n| language = Croatian\n| title = Newly elected members of the SDP governing bodies}}</ref> In July 2018 he and three other members of SDP presidency where suspended from their duties because of their dissatisfaction with the way party president [[Davor Bernardi\u0107]] leads SDP.<ref name= total-croatia-news />\n\n===Parliamentary career===\n\nIn 2011 parliamentary election, Grbin was elected in the Croatian Parliament for the first time. After [[Josip Leko]] was elected to the position of [[Speaker of Croatian Parliament]], Grbin was elected to the position of Chairman of the Committee on the Constitution, Standing Orders and Political System of the Croatian Parliament, where he served until the end of 2015. During his tenure as a committee chairman, Grbin was responsible for the preparation and adoption of the Act on the Co-Operation of the Croatian Parliament and the Government of the Republic of Croatian in European Affairs, new Standing Orders of the Croatian Parliament and 2015 amendments to Act on Election of Representatives to the Croatian Parliament.\n\nGrbin was reelected to Croatian Parliament in [[2015 Croatian parliamentary election|2015 parliamentary election]] and again in [[2016 Croatian parliamentary election|2016 parliamentary election]], where he now serves as a Deputy Chairman of the Committee on the Constitution, Standing Orders and Political System of the Croatian Parliament.<ref name= Biography />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grbin, Peda}}\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Croatia politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Pula]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:People from Istria]]\n[[Category:Representatives in the modern Croatian Parliament]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Croatian lawyer and politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name               = Pe\u0111a Grbin\n|image              = Pedja_Grbin.jpg\n|imagesize          = \n|caption            = \n|office             = [[Member of Parliament (Croatia)|Member of Parliament]]\n|term_start         = 22 December 2011\n|term_end           = \n|constituency       = VIII electoral district\n|office2            = Chairman of the Judiciary Committe of the Croatian Parliament\n|term_start2        = 28 February 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sabor.hr/en/members-parliament/grbin-peda-9-term |title=Hrvatski sabor |website=Sabor.hr |date= |accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|term_end2          =  \n|predecessor2       = [[Orsat Miljeni\u0107]]\n|successor2         = \n|office3            = Chairman of the Committee on the Constitution, Standing Orders and Political System of the Croatian Parliament\n|term_start3        = 12 October 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabor.hr/Default.aspx?art=50408 |title=Hrvatski sabor |website=Sabor.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-05-08}}</ref>\n|term_end3          = 28 December 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabor.hr/izbor-predsjednika-potpredsjednika-i-clanova-manda |title=Hrvatski sabor |website=Sabor.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-05-08}}</ref> \n|predecessor3       = [[Josip Leko]]\n|successor3         = [[Robert Podolnjak]]\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1979|05|24|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = [[Pula]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]]<br />{{small|(now [[Croatia]])}}\n|death_date         = \n|death_place        = \n|restingplace       = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|nationality        = [[Croatia]]n\n|party              = [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] (1998\u2013present)\n|spouse             = \n|children           = \n|alma_mater         = [[University of Zagreb]]\n|profession         = Lawyer\n|occupation         = Politician\n}}\n\n'''Pe\u0111a Grbin''' (born 24 May 1979) is a [[Croatia]]n lawyer and politician who represents [[Croatian Parliament electoral districts|VIII electoral district]] in the [[Croatian Parliament]] since 2011. He served as the Chairman of the Parliament's Committee on the Constitution, Standing Orders and Political System from 2012 until 2015.<ref name=\"Biography\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.sabor.hr/Default.aspx?sec=6260 |website=Sabor.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-05-08\n| language = English\n| title = Biography at the official web page of the Croatian Parliament\n}}</ref> He was vice president of the centre-left [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] (SDP) from 2016 to 2018 when he was suspended from that position.<ref name= \"Biography at www.biografija.com\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.biografija.com/peda-grbin/ |website=www.biografija.com |date= |accessdate=2017-11-17\n| language = Croatian\n| title = Pe\u0111a Grbin biografija}}</ref><ref name= total-croatia-news>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.total-croatia-news.com/politics/29783-sdp-suspends-senior-officials |website=www.total-croatia-news.com |date= |accessdate=2018-11-16\n| language = English\n| title = SDP Suspends Senior Officials}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and professional career==\nGrbin attended elementary and high school in [[Pula]], after which he enrolled in the [[Faculty of Law, University of Zagreb|Zagreb Faculty of Law]] from which he graduated in 2003. During elementary and high school days he played basketball for the local basketball team ''Gradine Pula''. After graduating, Grbin worked as a trainee in a law office and afterwards as an attorney from 2006 to 2011.<ref name= tportal>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/izbori2013/264633/Kako-SDP-ov-Veli-Joza-planira-poraziti-jakog-Miletica.html |website=tportal.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-05-08\n| language = Croatian\n| title = Kako SDP-ov Veli Jo\u017ee planira poraziti jakog Mileti\u0107a\n}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nAfter serving as a city councilor and a member of the municipal executive council in Pula, Grbin successfully ran in [[2011 Croatian parliamentary election|2011 parliamentary election]], and was elected to the Parliament in the VIII electoral district. He was reelected in [[2015 Croatian parliamentary election|2015]].<ref name= tportal />\n\n===Early career===\n\nGrbin joined SDP in 1998, and soon after that entered [[SDP Youth Forum]] where he was secretary general from 2001 to 2002. After graduating from law school he returned to Pula where he served first as a member of the municipal executive council from 2005 to 2009 and than as a city councilor from 2009 to 2013. Grbin was elected to the head committee of SDP in 2004 and has been a member of that party governing body until 2016 when he was elected to the party presidency.<ref name= sdp_izbori>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.sdp.hr/aktualno/izabrane-nove-clanice-clanovi-organa-sdp-a/ |website=sdp.hr |date= |accessdate=2016-05-08\n| language = Croatian\n| title = Newly elected members of the SDP governing bodies}}</ref> In July 2018 he and three other members of SDP presidency where suspended from their duties because of their dissatisfaction with the way party president [[Davor Bernardi\u0107]] leads SDP.<ref name= total-croatia-news />\n\n===Parliamentary career===\n\nIn 2011 parliamentary election, Grbin was elected in the Croatian Parliament for the first time. After [[Josip Leko]] was elected to the position of [[Speaker of Croatian Parliament]], Grbin was elected to the position of Chairman of the Committee on the Constitution, Standing Orders and Political System of the Croatian Parliament, where he served until the end of 2015. During his tenure as a committee chairman, Grbin was responsible for the preparation and adoption of the Act on the Co-Operation of the Croatian Parliament and the Government of the Republic of Croatian in European Affairs, new Standing Orders of the Croatian Parliament and 2015 amendments to Act on Election of Representatives to the Croatian Parliament.\n\nGrbin was reelected to Croatian Parliament in [[2015 Croatian parliamentary election|2015 parliamentary election]] and again in [[2016 Croatian parliamentary election|2016 parliamentary election]], where he now serves as a Deputy Chairman of the Committee on the Constitution, Standing Orders and Political System of the Croatian Parliament.<ref name= Biography />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grbin, Peda}}\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Croatia politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Pula]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:People from Istria]]\n[[Category:Representatives in the modern Croatian Parliament]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pe%C4%91a_Grbin"}
{"title_page": "Tontine", "text_new": "{{About|the financial instrument|the racehorse|Tontine (horse)|the Australian pillow manufacturer|Tontine Group}}\n{{confused|text = a [[dead pool]]}}\n[[File:Tontine Hotel sign, Ironbridge, UK.JPG|thumb|Tontine Hotel sign, [[Ironbridge]], Shropshire, UK]]\nA '''tontine''' (English pronunciation: {{IPAc-en|t|\u0252|n|t|i\u02d0|n}}) is an investment plan for raising capital, devised in the 17th century and relatively widespread in the 18th and 19th centuries. \n\nIt enables subscribers to share the risk of living a long life by combining features of a group [[Annuity (financial contracts)|annuity]] with a kind of mortality [[lottery]]. Each subscriber pays an agreed sum into the fund and thereafter receives a periodical payout. As members die, their payout entitlements devolve to the other participants, and so the value of each continuing payout increases. Typically, upon the death of the penultimate member, the scheme is wound up.\n\nTontines are regulated in Europe under the Directive 2002/83/EC of the European Parliament<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/en/ALL/?uri=CELEX:32002L0083|title=EUR-Lex - 32002L0083 - EN - EUR-Lex|website=eur-lex.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2017-10-17}}</ref> and are still common in [[France]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/international/3363847/Property-in-France-Keep-it-in-la-famille-now-and-for-ever.html|title=Property in France: Keep it in la famille now and for ever|last=Ingram|first=Miranda|date=2008-08-29|access-date=2017-10-16|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nThe new [[Pan-European Pension]] legislation coming into force in August 2020 contains provisions which specifically pave the way for a next-generation of pension products that abide by the \"tontine principle\".<ref name=\"meerten&hoog\">{{cite journal |last1=Meerten |first1=Hans van |last2=Hooghiemstra |first2=Sebastiaan Niels |title=PEPP \u2013 Towards a Harmonized European Legislative Framework for Personal Pensions |journal=SSRN |url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=2993991 |date=July 2017 }}</ref>\n\nQuestionable practices by U.S. life insurers in 1906 led to the [[Armstrong Investigation]] in the United States restricting some forms of tontines. Nevertheless, in March 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that tontines were getting fresh consideration as a way for people to get steady retirement income.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/24/business/retirement/tontines-retirement-annuity.html?_r=0 |title=When Others Die, Tontine Investors Win |website=nytimes.com |date=2017-03-24 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe investment plan is named after [[Naples|Neapolitan]] banker [[Lorenzo de Tonti]], who is popularly credited with inventing it in [[France]] in 1653. In fact, he more probably merely modified existing Italian investment schemes,<ref>Jennings; Swanson; Trout (1988), p. 107</ref> while another precursor was a proposal put to the Senate of [[Lisbon]] by Nicolas Bourey in 1641.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McKeever|first=Kent|date=10 February 2017 |title=A Tontine before Lorenzo de Tonti's! The Lisbon Tontine Proposal of 1641 |url=https://news.law.fordham.edu/jcfl/2017/02/10/a-tontine-before-lorenzo-de-tontis-the-lisbon-tontine-proposal-of-1641/|journal=Fordham Journal of Corporate & Financial Law Blog|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Tonti put his proposal to the French royal government, but after consideration it was rejected by the [[Parlement|Parlement de Paris]].<ref name=\"eb1911\">{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Tontine|volume=27}}</ref> The first true tontine was therefore organised in the city of [[Kampen, Overijssel|Kampen]] in the Netherlands in 1670. The French finally established a state tontine in 1689<ref name=\"eb1911\" /> (though it was not described by that name because Tonti had died in disgrace, about five years earlier). The English government organised a tontine in 1693.<ref name=\"Milevsky\">Milevsky 2015.</ref> Nine further government tontines were organised in France down to 1759; four more in Britain down to 1789; and others in the Netherlands and some of the German states. Those in Britain were not fully subscribed, and in general the British schemes tended to be less popular and successful than their continental counterparts.<ref>Weir 1989, pp. 95\u2013124</ref>\n\nBy the end of the 18th century, the tontine had fallen out of favour as a revenue-raising instrument with governments, but smaller-scale and less formal tontines continued to be arranged between individuals or to raise funds for specific projects throughout the 19th century, and, in modified form, to the present day.<ref name=nytimes/>\n\n==Concept==\nEach investor pays a sum into the tontine. Each investor then receives annual [[interest]] on the [[Financial capital|capital]] invested. As each investor dies, his or her share is reallocated among the surviving investors. This process continues until the death of the final investor, when the scheme is wound up. Each subscriber receives only interest; the capital is never paid back.<ref name=\"Weir103-4\">Weir 1989, pp. 103\u2013104</ref>\n\nStrictly speaking, the transaction involves four different roles:<ref name=\"Weir103-4\"/>\n\n# the government or corporate body which organizes the scheme, receives the loans and manages the capital\n# the subscribers who provide the capital\n# the shareholders who receive the annual interest\n# the nominees on whose lives the contracts are contingent\n\nIn most 18th- and 19th-century schemes, parties 2 to 4 were the same individuals; but in a significant minority of schemes each initial subscriber-shareholder was permitted to invest in the name of another party (generally one of his or her own children), who would inherit that share on the subscriber's death.<ref name=\"Weir103-4\"/>\n\nBecause younger nominees clearly had a longer life expectancy, the 17th- and 18th-century tontines were normally divided into several \"classes\" by age (typically in bands of 5, 7 or 10 years): each class effectively formed a separate tontine, with the shares of deceased members devolving to fellow-nominees within the same class.<ref name=\"Weir103-4\"/>\n\nIn a later variation, the capital devolves upon the last survivor, thus dissolving the trust and potentially making the survivor very wealthy.{{Citation needed|date = October 2016}} This version has often provided the plot device for mysteries and detective stories.\n\n==Patent==\n[[File:Dousset 1792.png|thumb|right|First page of Dousset 1792 French patent for a tontine]][[Business method patent|Financial inventions were patentable]] under French law from January 1791 until September 1792.  In June 1792 a patent was issued to inventor F. P. Dousset for a new type of tontine in combination with a [[lottery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cEYFAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA559#v=onepage&q=&f=false|title=Description des machines et proc\u00e9d\u00e9s sp\u00e9cifi\u00e9s dans les brevets d'invention, publ. par C.P. Molard. [With] Table g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des vingt premiers volumes. [Continued as] Description des machines ... pour lesquels des brevets d'invention ont \u00e9t\u00e9 pris sous le r\u00e9gime de la loi du 5 juillet 1844|first=France min du|last=commerce|date=30 April 2018|publisher=|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Uses and abuses==\n[[Louis XIV]] first made use of tontines in 1689 to fund military operations when he could not otherwise raise the money. The initial subscribers each put in 300 [[French livre|livres]] and, unlike most later schemes, this one was run honestly; the last survivor, a widow named Charlotte Barbier, who died in 1726 at the age of 96, received 73,000 livres in her last payment.<ref>Coudy 1957</ref><ref>Jennings and Trout 1982.</ref><ref name=\"Weir89\">Weir 1989.</ref> The English government first issued tontines in 1693 to fund a war against France, part of the [[Nine Years' War]].<ref name=\"Milevsky\"/><ref name=\"Weir89\"/>\n\nTontines soon caused financial problems for their issuing governments, as the organisers tended to underestimate the [[longevity]] of the population. At first, tontine holders included men and women of all ages. However, by the mid-18th century, investors were beginning to understand how to [[Gaming the system|game the system]], and it became increasingly common to buy tontine shares for young children, especially for girls around the age of 5 (since girls lived longer than boys, and by which age they were less at risk of infant mortality). This created the possibility of significant returns for the shareholders, with significant losses for the organizers. As a result, tontine schemes were eventually abandoned, and by the mid-1850s tontines had been replaced by other investment vehicles, such as \"[[penny policy|penny policies]]\", a predecessor of the 20th-century [[pension]] scheme.{{Citation needed|date = October 2016}}<!-- the previous paragraph mentions dishonestly-run tontines; there should be a discussion of those, too, and that phenomenon's role in the move to prohibit the tontine.-->\n\nA property development tontine, The Victoria Park Company, was at the heart of the notable case of ''[[Foss v Harbottle]]'' in mid-19th-century [[England]].{{Citation needed|date = October 2016}}\n\n==Projects funded by tontines==\n[[File:Tontine coffee house.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The [[Tontine Coffee House]] (at left) on [[Wall Street]], [[New York City]]]]\nTontines were often used to raise funds for private or [[public works]] projects.<ref>Green 2019.</ref> These sometimes contained the word \"tontine\" in their name.\n\nSome notable tontine-funded projects included:\n*[[Richmond Bridge, London|Richmond Bridge]], across the [[River Thames]] west of London, was financed using a tontine in 1774.\n*The Tontine Hotel in [[Ironbridge]], Shropshire, stands prominently at one end of the [[The Iron Bridge|Iron Bridge]] from which the town takes its name: it was built in 1780\u201384 by the proprietors of the bridge to accommodate tourists who came to view this wonder of the industrial age.\n*The [[Glasgow Cross|Tontine Hotel and Assembly Rooms]], [[Glasgow]], were funded through two tontine of 1781 and 1796.\n*The [[Tontine Coffee House]] on [[Wall Street]] in [[New York City]], built in 1792, was the first home of the [[New York Stock Exchange]].\n*The first [[Freemasons' Hall, London]]. Subscribers were able to nominate someone other than themselves as the person on whose life the share was staked.  On the subscriber's death they could leave their share to that person, or to anyone else. The scheme raised \u00a35,000, but cost \u00a321,750 in interest over its 87-year life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mqmagazine.co.uk/issue-19/p-52.php |title=MQ Magazine |volume=19 |publisher=United Grand Lodge of England}}</ref>\n*The Tontine Hotel, [[Greenock]], [[Inverclyde]], [[Scotland]], was built in 1803.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://data.historic-scotland.gov.uk/pls/htmldb/f?p=2200:15:0::::BUILDING:34078|title=Tontine Hotel, 5 Ardgowan Square: Listed Building Report |publisher=Historic Scotland}}</ref>\n*The Cleveland Tontine hotel, near [[Ingleby Arncliffe]], North Yorkshire, originally a [[coaching inn]] on the [[Yarm]] to [[Thirsk]] [[Turnpike trusts|turnpike road]], was financed using a tontine in 1804.<ref>{{cite web |title=About The Tontine: History of The Tontine |publisher=The Cleveland Tontine |url=https://www.theclevelandtontine.com/about/ |accessdate=28 February 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Tontine pensions in the US: 1868\u20131906==\nTontines became associated with life insurance in the United States in 1868 when [[Henry Baldwin Hyde]] of the [[AXA Equitable Life Insurance Company|Equitable Life Assurance Society]] introduced them as a means of selling more life insurance and meeting the demands of competition. Over the next four decades, the Equitable and its imitators sold approximately 9 million policies \u2013 two-thirds of the nation's outstanding insurance contracts. During the [[Panic of 1873]] many life insurance companies went out of business as deteriorating financial conditions created solvency problems: those that survived had all offered tontines.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Yang |first1=Tony |date=2009 |page=5 |title=The Performance of Life Insurance Companies: 1860\u20131905 |url=http://www.americasmutualbanks.com/images/0714_YangPaper.pdf }}</ref> However, the contracts included an obligation to maintain monthly payments, and as a result spawned large numbers of policy owners whose life savings were wiped out by a single missed payment. The profits produced by the tontines' deferred payout structures proved tempting for the issuers \u2013 especially the profligate [[James Hazen Hyde|James Hyde]]. As the funds in the investment account accumulated, they found their way into directors' and agents' pockets, and also into the hands of judges and legislators, who reciprocated with prejudicial judgments and laws.<ref>{{cite journal |first=William J. |last=Bernstein |title=King William's Tontine: Why the Retirement Annuity of the Future Should Resemble Its Past (a review) |journal=Financial Analysts Journal |publisher=CFA Institute |volume=10 |issue=1 |year=2015 |url=https://www.cfapubs.org/doi/full/10.2469/br.v10.n1.17 |accessdate=11 May 2018 |doi=10.2469/br.v10.n1.17 |doi-broken-date=2019-12-16 }}</ref> \n\nFinally, in 1905, the [[Armstrong Investigation]] was set up to enquire into the selling of tontines. It resulted in the banning of the continued sale of those tontines which contained toxic clauses for consumers.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Moss |first1=David |first2=Eugene |last2=Kintgen |title=The Armstrong Investigation |journal=Harvard Business School Case Collection |volume=708-034 |origyear=January 2008 |date=January 2009 |url=https://www.hbs.edu/faculty/Pages/item.aspx?num=35348 |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism from competitors==\nWhen Equitable Life Assurance was establishing its business in Australia in the 1880s, an actuary of the [[AMP Limited|Australian Mutual Provident Society]] criticised tontine insurance, calling it \"an immoral contract\" which \"put a premium on murder\".<ref>Buley 1967, p. 291.</ref> In New Zealand at the time, another of the chief critics of tontines had been the government, which also issued its own insurance.<ref>Buley 1967, p. 472.</ref>\n\n==Modern regulation==\nUntil recently, the First Life Directive of the European Union specified tontines as a class of insurance business however the new [[Pan-European Pension]] legislation coming into force in August 2020 specifically paves the way for non-insurance operators to create new pension products that abide by the \"tontine principle\".<ref name=\"meerten&hoog\"/>\n\nIn most places in the United States using tontines to raise capital or obtain lifetime income is consistently upheld as being legal; however, outdated legislation in two states has fostered the incorrect perception that selling tontines in the broader U.S. is illegal.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tardi |first1=Carla |title=Tontine |url=https://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/tontine.asp |website=Investopedia}}</ref>\n\n==Tontine pensions==\nIn 2015, John Barry Forman and Michael J. Sabin, using modern actuarial techniques to calculate fair transfer payments when participants are of different ages and have made different contributions, proposed a new structure of [[pension]] plan on the tontine model, through which large employers could provide retirement income for their employees. They argued that tontine pensions would have two major advantages over traditional pensions, as they would always be fully funded, and the plan sponsor would not be required to bear the investment and actuarial risks.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.pennlawreview.com/print/163-U-Pa-L-Rev-755.pdf |first1=John Barry |last1=Forman |first2= Michael J. |last2=Sabin |title=Tontine Pensions |journal=[[University of Pennsylvania Law Review]] |volume=163 |issue=3 |year=2015 |pages=755\u2013831 }}</ref> Similar arguments were put forward in the same year by [[Moshe Milevsky]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=King William's Tontine: Why the Retirement Annuity of the Future Should Resemble its Past|last=Milevsky|first=Moshe A.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2015|isbn=978-1107076129|location=|pages=170\u201397}}</ref> In March 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that tontines were getting fresh consideration as a way for people to get steady retirement income.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Dean McClelland, Richard Fullmer and Jon Matonis and others published a whitepaper to deliver secure low cost Tontine Pensions based loosely upon the Forman, Sabin and Milevsky format under the brand [[TontineTrust]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tontine.com/whitepaper-nt/TontineTrust.Non-Technical.Whitepaper.(V1.01D).pdf|title=Tontine Trust - Retirement Planning for the 21st Century|last=McClelland|first=Dean|date=November 15, 2017|website=Tontine.com}}</ref>  In 2018, Richard K. Fullmer and Michael J. Sabin expanded on the ideas presented in Forman and Sabin (2015) by showing that participants in an actuarially fair tontine need not be confined to a common investment portfolio or to a common payout method. Their paper introduced the concept of individual tontine accounts (ITAs), which they envisioned as complementary to individual retirement account (IRAs).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=3217551|title=Individual Tontine Accounts|last=Fullmer|first=Richard K.|last2=Sabin|first2=Michael J.|date=July 21, 2018|website=SSRN}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the [[CFA Institute]] Research Foundation published a research brief titled ''Tontines: A Practitioner's Guide to Mortality-Pooled Investments'' noting that \"the study of fair tontine design is a specialty all its own\u2014one that has emerged only recently.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.cfainstitute.org/-/media/documents/article/rf-brief/fullmer-tontines-rf-brief.ashx|title=Tontines: A Practitioner's Guide to Mortality-Pooled Investments|last=Fullmer|first=Richard K.|publisher=CFA Institute Research Foundation|year=2019|isbn=978-1-944960-75-9|location=|pages=}}</ref> Fullmer and Sabin showed that it is possible to engineer payouts within a tontine structure that are immune to interest rate and reinvestment risk.<ref>Fullmer, Richard K. and Sabin, Michael J. (April 16, 2019). [https://ssrn.com/abstract=3373251 Tontine Bond Ladders]. Available at SSRN.</ref>\n\n==Variant uses of the term==\nIn French-speaking cultures, particularly in [[Developing country|developing countries]], the meaning of the term \"tontine\" has broadened to encompass a wider range of semi-formal group savings and [[microcredit]] schemes. The crucial difference between these and tontines in the traditional sense is that benefits do not depend on the deaths of other members.\n\nIn the UK during the mid-20th century, the term was applied to communal Christmas saving schemes, with participants making regular payments of an agreed sum through the year, which would be withdrawn shortly before Christmas to fund gifts and festivities.<ref>For a description and images of a contribution card, see {{cite web |title=Rhostyllen: a history through pictures |url=http://rhostyllen.info/misc.html |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAs a type of [[Rotating Savings and Credit Association|rotating savings and credit association]] (ROSCA), tontines are well established as a savings instrument in central Africa, and in this case function as savings clubs in which each member makes regular payments and is lent the [[wiktionary:kitty#noun|kitty]] in turn. They are wound up after each cycle of loans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ecole.org/seminaires/FS3/SEM105/VC190603-ENG.pdf |title=Using tontines to run the economy |first=Alain |last=Henry |publisher=l'\u00c9cole de Paris du management |date=June 19, 2003}}</ref> In West Africa, \"tontines\" \u2013 often consisting of mainly women \u2013 are an example of economic, social and cultural solidarity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dandc.eu/en/article/self-organised-savings-communities-tontines-are-example-economic-social-and-cultural |title=Flexible and disciplined |first=Eva-Maria |last=Bruchhaus |publisher=D+C, Development and Cooperation |date=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nInformal group savings and loan associations are also traditional in many east Asian societies, and under the name of tontines are found in [[Cambodia]], and among emigrant Cambodian communities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cambodia.org.nz/Tontine.htm |title=Tontine: an alternative financial instrument in Cambodian communities |first=Man Hau |last=Liev |publisher=12th NZASIA Conference |date=November 26\u201329, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Singapore]], the Chit Funds Act of 1971<ref>{{cite web |title=Chit Funds Act |work=Singapore Statutes Online |origyear=1971 |year=2013 |url=https://sso.agc.gov.sg/Act/CFA1971 |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref> defines the application of legislation to the operation of [[chit fund]]s, which were also known colloquially as tontines but which operated on a different principle more commonly known as a ROSCA ([[Rotating Savings and Credit Association]]).\n \nIn [[Malaysia]], chit funds are primarily known as \"kootu funds\", which again are ROSCAs and which are defined under the ''Kootu Funds (Prohibition) Act 1971'' as \n\"...a scheme or arrangement variously known as a kootu, cheetu, chit fund, hwei, tontine or otherwise whereby the participants subscribe periodically or otherwise to a common fund and such common fund is put up for sale or payment to the participants by auction, tender, bid, ballot or otherwise...\" <ref>{{cite web |title=Kootu Funds (Prohibition) Act 1971 |work=Commonwealth Legal Information Institute |year=1971 |url=http://www.commonlii.org/my/legis/consol_act/kfa1971281/ |accessdate=27 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nTontines have been featured as plot devices in many fictional stories, movies and television programs, including:\n*''La Tontine'' (1708), a comic play by [[Alain-Ren\u00e9 Lesage]]. A physician, hoping to raise the funds to give his daughter a dowry, buys a tontine on the life of an elderly peasant, who he then strives to keep alive.\n*''The Great Tontine'' (1881), is a novel by [[Henry Hawley Smart|Hawley Smart]].\n*''[[The Wrong Box (novel)|The Wrong Box]]'' (1889), is a comic novel by [[Robert Louis Stevenson]] and [[Lloyd Osbourne]]. The plot revolves around a tontine originally taken out for some wealthy English children, and the resulting shenanigans as younger family members of the two final survivors vie to secure the final payout. The book was adapted as a [[The Wrong Box|film]], produced and directed by [[Bryan Forbes]], (1966).\n*''The Secret Tontine'' (1912), is an atmospheric faux-gothic novel by [[Robert Murray Gilchrist]], set in the [[Derbyshire]] [[Peak District]] during a snowy winter in the late 19th century. The plot involves the potential beneficiaries of a covert tontine, and their scheme to murder their ignorant rivals. \n*[[Lillian de la Torre]]'s short story \"The Tontine Curse\" (1948) features mysterious deaths related to a tontine in 1779, being investigated by [[Samuel Johnson]].\n*''The Tontine'' (1955), a novel by [[Thomas B. Costain]], illustrated by [[Herbert Ryman]], is set in nineteenth-century England and tells a story centered around the fictional \"Waterloo Tontine\", established to benefit veterans of the Napoleonic wars. Among other plot twists, shareholders hire an actor to impersonate a dead nominee, and conspire to murder another member.\n*In ''[[4.50 from Paddington]]'' (1957), a [[Miss Marple]] murder mystery by [[Agatha Christie]], the plot revolves around the will of a wealthy industrialist, which establishes a [[Settlement (trust)|settlement]] under which his estate is divided in trust among his grandchildren, the final survivor to inherit the whole. The settlement is described, inaccurately, as a tontine. \n*''[[Something Fishy]]'' (1957), a novel by [[P. G. Wodehouse]], features a so-called tontine under which the investors' sons stand to gain from marrying late.\n* In the U.S. television series ''[[The Wild Wild West]]'', Episode 16 of Season Two (1966\u201367) \u2013 \"The Night of the Tottering Tontine\" \u2013 finds James West and Artemus Gordon protecting a man who is a member of a tontine whose members are being murdered one by another.\n*\"Old Soldiers,\" an eighth-season episode of the television series ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'', focuses on a tontine set up among Colonel Potter and several of his Army buddies from [[World War I]]. While taking shelter in a ch\u00e2teau during an artillery barrage, they had found a cache of brandy and drank all but one bottle, which they set aside for the last survivor. After the only other surviving member dies, Potter receives the bottle in the mail and shares it with his staff, drinking first to his departed friends and then to the new ones he has made at the 4077th.\n*In the ''[[Barney Miller]]'' episode \"The Tontine\" (1982), one of the last two surviving family members who invested in the tontine attempts to kill himself so that the other can have the money before growing too old to enjoy it.\n* In ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Raging Abe Simpson and His Grumbling Grandson in \"The Curse of the Flying Hellfish\"]]\" (1996), [[Grampa Simpson]] and [[Mr. Burns]] are the final survivors of a tontine to determine ownership of art looted during [[World War II]]. Grampa eventually kicks Burns out of the tontine for trying to kill him, but before he and Bart can do anything with the art, a descendant of the original owner shows up to claim it.\n*In [[S. L. Viehl]]'s science fiction multi-volume novel ''Stardoc'' (2000), the title character is accused of spreading a plague to several colony worlds, on one of which the colonists had established a tontine. The sole survivor, a little girl, consequently becomes so wealthy that in the second book of the series \u2013 ''Beyond Varallan'' (2000) \u2013 she buys the bank behind the colonies to free the Stardoc from the debt she now owes.\n*The 2001 comedy film ''[[Tomcats (2001 film)|Tomcats]]'' features a variation on a tontine where the last investor to get married gets the full amount of the invested funds.\n* In the ''[[Archer (2009 TV series)|Archer]]'' episode \"The Double Deuce\" (2011), Archer's [[valet]] Woodhouse is revealed as one of three final survivors of a group of World War I [[Royal Flying Corps]] squadron mates who each put [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]50 into an interest-bearing account, now worth nearly a million [[United States dollar|dollars]]. The office workers at ISIS HQ, realizing that a new tontine could capitalize on the high mortality rate of field agents, begin persuading people to join.\n* The ''[[Diagnosis: Murder]]'' episode \"Being of Sound Mind\" (Season 8 Episode 16) features a tontine as a motive for murder.\n*The ''[[The Brokenwood Mysteries|Brokenwood Mysteries]]'' episode \"Tontine\" (Season 5 Episode 3) centres on a tontine.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last=Buley|first=R. Carlyle|title=The Equitable Life Assurance Society of the United States 1859\u20131964|date=1967|publisher=Appleton-Century-Crofts|location=New York}}\n*{{cite book |first=Geoffrey |last=Clark |title=Betting on Lives: the culture of life insurance in England, 1695\u20131775 |location=Manchester |publisher=Manchester University Press |year=1999 |isbn=9780719056758 }} \n*{{Cite journal |first=Julien |last=Coudy |title=La Tontine royal sous le r\u00e8gne de Louis XIV |journal=Revue historique de droit fran\u00e7ais et \u00e9tranger |volume=4th ser. 35 |year=1957 |pages=128\u201333 |language=fr}}\n*{{Cite journal |first=John |last=Dunkley |title=Bourbons on the Rocks: tontines and early public lotteries in France |journal=Journal for Eighteenth-Century Studies |volume=30 |issue=3 |year=2007 |pages=309\u201323 |doi=10.1111/j.1754-0208.2007.tb00338.x}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Gallais Hamonno |first1=Georges |last2=Berthon |first2=Jean |title=Les emprunts tontiniers de l'Ancien R\u00e9gime: un exemple d'ing\u00e9nierie financi\u00e8re au XVIIIe si\u00e8cle |location=Paris |year=2008 |language=fr}}\n*{{cite journal|first=David R. |last=Green |title=Tontines, annuities and civic improvements in Georgian Britain |journal=Urban History |volume=46 |issue=4 |year=2019 |pages=649\u201394 |doi=10.1017/s0963926818000743 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last1=Jennings |first1=Robert M. |last2=Trout |first2=Andrew P. |title=The Tontine: fact and fiction |journal=Journal of European Economic History |volume=5 |year=1976 |pages=663\u201370 }}\n*{{Cite book |last1=Jennings |first1=Robert M. |last2=Trout |first2=Andrew P. |title=The Tontine: from the reign of Louis XIV to the French Revolutionary era |location=Homewood, IL |year=1982 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last1=Jennings |first1=Robert M. |last2=Swanson |first2=Donald F. |last3=Trout |first3=Andrew P. |title=Alexander Hamilton's tontine proposal |journal=William and Mary Quarterly |series=3rd ser. |volume=45 |issue=1 |year=1988 |pages=107\u2013115 |jstor=1922216|doi=10.2307/1922216 }}\n*{{Cite journal |url=http://ir.lawnet.fordham.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1108&context=jcfl&sei-redir=1#search=%22fordham%20tontines%22 |first=Kent |last=McKeever |title=A Short History of Tontines |journal=[[Fordham Journal of Corporate & Financial Law]] |volume=15 |issue=2 |year=2011 |pages=491\u2013521}}\n*{{cite book |last=Milevsky |first=Moshe A. |authorlink=Moshe Milevsky |title=King William's Tontine: why the retirement annuity of the future should resemble its past |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |year=2015 |isbn=978-110-707612-9}}\n*{{Cite journal |first=David R. |last=Weir |title=Tontines, Public Finance, and Revolution in France and England, 1688\u20131789 |journal=Journal of Economic History |volume=49 |year=1989 |pages=95\u2013124 |doi=10.1017/s002205070000735x|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/6b6216730f9bb206697414ac38327061feb3673d }}\n*{{Cite book|author=Wyler, Julius |title=Die Tontinen in Frankreich |location=Munich and Leipzig |year=1916 |language=de}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|tontine}}\n*[[wikisource:The Story of Life Insurance/Chapter IV|\"The Great Tontine Gamble\"]], one of a series of articles by [[Burton J. Hendrick]] appearing in ''[[McClure's Magazine]]'' in 1906\n*[http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a3_172.html ''The Straight Dope'': \"What's with tontines, the odd annuities in which you benefit when others die?\"]\n*[http://www.cato.org/pubs/regulation/regv32n4/v32n4-4.pdf Baker et al. (Winter 2009-2010) \"Tontines for the Young Invincibles\", ''Regulation'']\n*[https://www.forbes.com/sites/pensionresearchcouncil/2018/01/30/fintechs-answer-to-the-global-retirement-crisis/#586b0cd31ff3 \"Forbes  Pensions Research Council (Jan 18, 2018) \"Fintech's Answer To The Global Retirement Crisis\"]\n\n{{Economic history of the Netherlands}}\n\n[[Category:Investment]]\n[[Category:Informal finance]]\n[[Category:1653 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:17th-century introductions]]\n[[Category:Economic history of the Netherlands]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the financial instrument|the racehorse|Tontine (horse)|the Australian pillow manufacturer|Tontine Group}}\n{{confused|text = a [[dead pool]]}}\n[[File:Tontine Hotel sign, Ironbridge, UK.JPG|thumb|Tontine Hotel sign, [[Ironbridge]], Shropshire, UK]]\nA '''tontine''' (English pronunciation: {{IPAc-en|t|\u0252|n|t|i\u02d0|n}}) is an investment plan for raising capital, devised in the 17th century and relatively widespread in the 18th and 19th centuries. \n\nIt enables subscribers to share the risk of living a long life by combining features of a group [[Annuity (financial contracts)|annuity]] with a kind of mortality [[lottery]]. Each subscriber pays an agreed sum into the fund and thereafter receives a periodical payout. As members die, their payout entitlements devolve to the other participants, and so the value of each continuing payout increases. Typically, upon the death of the penultimate member, the scheme is wound up.\n\nTontines are regulated in Europe under the Directive 2002/83/EC of the European Parliament<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/en/ALL/?uri=CELEX:32002L0083|title=EUR-Lex - 32002L0083 - EN - EUR-Lex|website=eur-lex.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2017-10-17}}</ref> and are still common in [[France]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/international/3363847/Property-in-France-Keep-it-in-la-famille-now-and-for-ever.html|title=Property in France: Keep it in la famille now and for ever|last=Ingram|first=Miranda|date=2008-08-29|access-date=2017-10-16|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nThe new [[Pan-European Pension]] legislation coming into force in August 2020 contains provisions which specifically pave the way for a next-generation of pension products that abide by the \u2018tontine principle\u2019 <ref> last = Hooghiemstra | first = Sebastiaan Niels | title = PEPP \u2013 Towards a Harmonized European Legislative Framework for Personal Pensions | journal = SSRN | url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=2993991 | date = July 2017 </ref>.\n\nQuestionable practices by U.S. life insurers in 1906 led to the [[Armstrong Investigation]] in the United States restricting some forms of tontines. Nevertheless, in March 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that tontines were getting fresh consideration as a way for people to get steady retirement income.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/24/business/retirement/tontines-retirement-annuity.html?_r=0 |title=When Others Die, Tontine Investors Win |website=nytimes.com |date=2017-03-24 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe investment plan is named after [[Naples|Neapolitan]] banker [[Lorenzo de Tonti]], who is popularly credited with inventing it in [[France]] in 1653. In fact, he more probably merely modified existing Italian investment schemes,<ref>Jennings; Swanson; Trout (1988), p. 107</ref> while another precursor was a proposal put to the Senate of [[Lisbon]] by Nicolas Bourey in 1641.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McKeever|first=Kent|date=10 February 2017 |title=A Tontine before Lorenzo de Tonti's! The Lisbon Tontine Proposal of 1641 |url=https://news.law.fordham.edu/jcfl/2017/02/10/a-tontine-before-lorenzo-de-tontis-the-lisbon-tontine-proposal-of-1641/|journal=Fordham Journal of Corporate & Financial Law Blog|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Tonti put his proposal to the French royal government, but after consideration it was rejected by the [[Parlement|Parlement de Paris]].<ref name=\"eb1911\">{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Tontine|volume=27}}</ref> The first true tontine was therefore organised in the city of [[Kampen, Overijssel|Kampen]] in the Netherlands in 1670. The French finally established a state tontine in 1689<ref name=\"eb1911\" /> (though it was not described by that name because Tonti had died in disgrace, about five years earlier). The English government organised a tontine in 1693.<ref name=\"Milevsky\">Milevsky 2015.</ref> Nine further government tontines were organised in France down to 1759; four more in Britain down to 1789; and others in the Netherlands and some of the German states. Those in Britain were not fully subscribed, and in general the British schemes tended to be less popular and successful than their continental counterparts.<ref>Weir 1989, pp. 95\u2013124</ref>\n\nBy the end of the 18th century, the tontine had fallen out of favour as a revenue-raising instrument with governments, but smaller-scale and less formal tontines continued to be arranged between individuals or to raise funds for specific projects throughout the 19th century, and, in modified form, to the present day.<ref name=nytimes/>\n\n==Concept==\nEach investor pays a sum into the tontine. Each investor then receives annual [[interest]] on the [[Financial capital|capital]] invested. As each investor dies, his or her share is reallocated among the surviving investors. This process continues until the death of the final investor, when the scheme is wound up. Each subscriber receives only interest; the capital is never paid back.<ref name=\"Weir103-4\">Weir 1989, pp. 103\u2013104</ref>\n\nStrictly speaking, the transaction involves four different roles:<ref name=\"Weir103-4\"/>\n\n# the government or corporate body which organizes the scheme, receives the loans and manages the capital\n# the subscribers who provide the capital\n# the shareholders who receive the annual interest\n# the nominees on whose lives the contracts are contingent\n\nIn most 18th- and 19th-century schemes, parties 2 to 4 were the same individuals; but in a significant minority of schemes each initial subscriber-shareholder was permitted to invest in the name of another party (generally one of his or her own children), who would inherit that share on the subscriber's death.<ref name=\"Weir103-4\"/>\n\nBecause younger nominees clearly had a longer life expectancy, the 17th- and 18th-century tontines were normally divided into several \"classes\" by age (typically in bands of 5, 7 or 10 years): each class effectively formed a separate tontine, with the shares of deceased members devolving to fellow-nominees within the same class.<ref name=\"Weir103-4\"/>\n\nIn a later variation, the capital devolves upon the last survivor, thus dissolving the trust and potentially making the survivor very wealthy.{{Citation needed|date = October 2016}} This version has often provided the plot device for mysteries and detective stories.\n\n==Patent==\n[[File:Dousset 1792.png|thumb|right|First page of Dousset 1792 French patent for a tontine]][[Business method patent|Financial inventions were patentable]] under French law from January 1791 until September 1792.  In June 1792 a patent was issued to inventor F. P. Dousset for a new type of tontine in combination with a [[lottery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cEYFAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA559#v=onepage&q=&f=false|title=Description des machines et proc\u00e9d\u00e9s sp\u00e9cifi\u00e9s dans les brevets d'invention, publ. par C.P. Molard. [With] Table g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des vingt premiers volumes. [Continued as] Description des machines ... pour lesquels des brevets d'invention ont \u00e9t\u00e9 pris sous le r\u00e9gime de la loi du 5 juillet 1844|first=France min du|last=commerce|date=30 April 2018|publisher=|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Uses and abuses==\n[[Louis XIV]] first made use of tontines in 1689 to fund military operations when he could not otherwise raise the money. The initial subscribers each put in 300 [[French livre|livres]] and, unlike most later schemes, this one was run honestly; the last survivor, a widow named Charlotte Barbier, who died in 1726 at the age of 96, received 73,000 livres in her last payment.<ref>Coudy 1957</ref><ref>Jennings and Trout 1982.</ref><ref name=\"Weir89\">Weir 1989.</ref> The English government first issued tontines in 1693 to fund a war against France, part of the [[Nine Years' War]].<ref name=\"Milevsky\"/><ref name=\"Weir89\"/>\n\nTontines soon caused financial problems for their issuing governments, as the organisers tended to underestimate the [[longevity]] of the population. At first, tontine holders included men and women of all ages. However, by the mid-18th century, investors were beginning to understand how to [[Gaming the system|game the system]], and it became increasingly common to buy tontine shares for young children, especially for girls around the age of 5 (since girls lived longer than boys, and by which age they were less at risk of infant mortality). This created the possibility of significant returns for the shareholders, with significant losses for the organizers. As a result, tontine schemes were eventually abandoned, and by the mid-1850s tontines had been replaced by other investment vehicles, such as \"[[penny policy|penny policies]]\", a predecessor of the 20th-century [[pension]] scheme.{{Citation needed|date = October 2016}}<!-- the previous paragraph mentions dishonestly-run tontines; there should be a discussion of those, too, and that phenomenon's role in the move to prohibit the tontine.-->\n\nA property development tontine, The Victoria Park Company, was at the heart of the notable case of ''[[Foss v Harbottle]]'' in mid-19th-century [[England]].{{Citation needed|date = October 2016}}\n\n==Projects funded by tontines==\n[[File:Tontine coffee house.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The [[Tontine Coffee House]] (at left) on [[Wall Street]], [[New York City]]]]\nTontines were often used to raise funds for private or [[public works]] projects.<ref>Green 2019.</ref> These sometimes contained the word \"tontine\" in their name.\n\nSome notable tontine-funded projects included:\n*[[Richmond Bridge, London|Richmond Bridge]], across the [[River Thames]] west of London, was financed using a tontine in 1774.\n*The Tontine Hotel in [[Ironbridge]], Shropshire, stands prominently at one end of the [[The Iron Bridge|Iron Bridge]] from which the town takes its name: it was built in 1780\u201384 by the proprietors of the bridge to accommodate tourists who came to view this wonder of the industrial age.\n*The [[Glasgow Cross|Tontine Hotel and Assembly Rooms]], [[Glasgow]], were funded through two tontine of 1781 and 1796.\n*The [[Tontine Coffee House]] on [[Wall Street]] in [[New York City]], built in 1792, was the first home of the [[New York Stock Exchange]].\n*The first [[Freemasons' Hall, London]]. Subscribers were able to nominate someone other than themselves as the person on whose life the share was staked.  On the subscriber's death they could leave their share to that person, or to anyone else. The scheme raised \u00a35,000, but cost \u00a321,750 in interest over its 87-year life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mqmagazine.co.uk/issue-19/p-52.php |title=MQ Magazine |volume=19 |publisher=United Grand Lodge of England}}</ref>\n*The Tontine Hotel, [[Greenock]], [[Inverclyde]], [[Scotland]], was built in 1803.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://data.historic-scotland.gov.uk/pls/htmldb/f?p=2200:15:0::::BUILDING:34078|title=Tontine Hotel, 5 Ardgowan Square: Listed Building Report |publisher=Historic Scotland}}</ref>\n*The Cleveland Tontine hotel, near [[Ingleby Arncliffe]], North Yorkshire, originally a [[coaching inn]] on the [[Yarm]] to [[Thirsk]] [[Turnpike trusts|turnpike road]], was financed using a tontine in 1804.<ref>{{cite web |title=About The Tontine: History of The Tontine |publisher=The Cleveland Tontine |url=https://www.theclevelandtontine.com/about/ |accessdate=28 February 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Tontine pensions in the US: 1868\u20131906==\nTontines became associated with life insurance in the United States in 1868 when [[Henry Baldwin Hyde]] of the [[AXA Equitable Life Insurance Company|Equitable Life Assurance Society]] introduced them as a means of selling more life insurance and meeting the demands of competition. Over the next four decades, the Equitable and its imitators sold approximately 9 million policies \u2013 two-thirds of the nation's outstanding insurance contracts. During the [[Panic of 1873]] many life insurance companies went out of business as deteriorating financial conditions created solvency problems: those that survived had all offered tontines.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Yang |first1=Tony |date=2009 |page=5 |title=The Performance of Life Insurance Companies: 1860\u20131905 |url=http://www.americasmutualbanks.com/images/0714_YangPaper.pdf }}</ref> However, the contracts included an obligation to maintain monthly payments, and as a result spawned large numbers of policy owners whose life savings were wiped out by a single missed payment. The profits produced by the tontines' deferred payout structures proved tempting for the issuers \u2013 especially the profligate [[James Hazen Hyde|James Hyde]]. As the funds in the investment account accumulated, they found their way into directors' and agents' pockets, and also into the hands of judges and legislators, who reciprocated with prejudicial judgments and laws.<ref>{{cite journal |first=William J. |last=Bernstein |title=King William's Tontine: Why the Retirement Annuity of the Future Should Resemble Its Past (a review) |journal=Financial Analysts Journal |publisher=CFA Institute |volume=10 |issue=1 |year=2015 |url=https://www.cfapubs.org/doi/full/10.2469/br.v10.n1.17 |accessdate=11 May 2018 |doi=10.2469/br.v10.n1.17 |doi-broken-date=2019-12-16 }}</ref> \n\nFinally, in 1905, the [[Armstrong Investigation]] was set up to enquire into the selling of tontines. It resulted in the banning of the continued sale of those tontines which contained toxic clauses for consumers.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Moss |first1=David |first2=Eugene |last2=Kintgen |title=The Armstrong Investigation |journal=Harvard Business School Case Collection |volume=708-034 |origyear=January 2008 |date=January 2009 |url=https://www.hbs.edu/faculty/Pages/item.aspx?num=35348 |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism from competitors==\nWhen Equitable Life Assurance was establishing its business in Australia in the 1880s, an actuary of the [[AMP Limited|Australian Mutual Provident Society]] criticised tontine insurance, calling it \"an immoral contract\" which \"put a premium on murder\".<ref>Buley 1967, p. 291.</ref> In New Zealand at the time, another of the chief critics of tontines had been the government, which also issued its own insurance.<ref>Buley 1967, p. 472.</ref>\n\n==Modern regulation==\nUntil recently, the First Life Directive of the European Union specified tontines as a class of insurance business however the new [[Pan-European Pension]] legislation coming into force in August 2020 specifically paves the way for non-insurance operators to create new pension products that abide by the \u2018tontine principle\u2019. <ref>https://dx.doi.org/10.2139/ssrn.2993991</ref>\n\nIn most places in the United States using tontines to raise capital or obtain lifetime income is consistently upheld as being legal; however, outdated legislation in two states has fostered the incorrect perception that selling tontines in the broader U.S. is illegal.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tardi |first1=Carla |title=Tontine |url=https://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/tontine.asp |website=Investopedia}}</ref>\n\n==Tontine pensions==\nIn 2015, John Barry Forman and Michael J. Sabin, using modern actuarial techniques to calculate fair transfer payments when participants are of different ages and have made different contributions, proposed a new structure of [[pension]] plan on the tontine model, through which large employers could provide retirement income for their employees. They argued that tontine pensions would have two major advantages over traditional pensions, as they would always be fully funded, and the plan sponsor would not be required to bear the investment and actuarial risks.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.pennlawreview.com/print/163-U-Pa-L-Rev-755.pdf |first1=John Barry |last1=Forman |first2= Michael J. |last2=Sabin |title=Tontine Pensions |journal=[[University of Pennsylvania Law Review]] |volume=163 |issue=3 |year=2015 |pages=755\u2013831 }}</ref> Similar arguments were put forward in the same year by [[Moshe Milevsky]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=King William's Tontine: Why the Retirement Annuity of the Future Should Resemble its Past|last=Milevsky|first=Moshe A.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2015|isbn=978-1107076129|location=|pages=170\u201397}}</ref> In March 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that tontines were getting fresh consideration as a way for people to get steady retirement income.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Dean McClelland, Richard Fullmer and Jon Matonis and others published a whitepaper to deliver secure low cost Tontine Pensions based loosely upon the Forman, Sabin and Milevsky format under the brand [[TontineTrust]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tontine.com/whitepaper-nt/TontineTrust.Non-Technical.Whitepaper.(V1.01D).pdf|title=Tontine Trust - Retirement Planning for the 21st Century|last=McClelland|first=Dean|date=November 15, 2017|website=Tontine.com}}</ref>  In 2018, Richard K. Fullmer and Michael J. Sabin expanded on the ideas presented in Forman and Sabin (2015) by showing that participants in an actuarially fair tontine need not be confined to a common investment portfolio or to a common payout method. Their paper introduced the concept of individual tontine accounts (ITAs), which they envisioned as complementary to individual retirement account (IRAs).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=3217551|title=Individual Tontine Accounts|last=Fullmer|first=Richard K.|last2=Sabin|first2=Michael J.|date=July 21, 2018|website=SSRN}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the [[CFA Institute]] Research Foundation published a research brief titled ''Tontines: A Practitioner's Guide to Mortality-Pooled Investments'' noting that \"the study of fair tontine design is a specialty all its own\u2014one that has emerged only recently.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.cfainstitute.org/-/media/documents/article/rf-brief/fullmer-tontines-rf-brief.ashx|title=Tontines: A Practitioner's Guide to Mortality-Pooled Investments|last=Fullmer|first=Richard K.|publisher=CFA Institute Research Foundation|year=2019|isbn=978-1-944960-75-9|location=|pages=}}</ref> Fullmer and Sabin showed that it is possible to engineer payouts within a tontine structure that are immune to interest rate and reinvestment risk.<ref>Fullmer, Richard K. and Sabin, Michael J. (April 16, 2019). [https://ssrn.com/abstract=3373251 Tontine Bond Ladders]. Available at SSRN.</ref>\n\n==Variant uses of the term==\nIn French-speaking cultures, particularly in [[Developing country|developing countries]], the meaning of the term \"tontine\" has broadened to encompass a wider range of semi-formal group savings and [[microcredit]] schemes. The crucial difference between these and tontines in the traditional sense is that benefits do not depend on the deaths of other members.\n\nIn the UK during the mid-20th century, the term was applied to communal Christmas saving schemes, with participants making regular payments of an agreed sum through the year, which would be withdrawn shortly before Christmas to fund gifts and festivities.<ref>For a description and images of a contribution card, see {{cite web |title=Rhostyllen: a history through pictures |url=http://rhostyllen.info/misc.html |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAs a type of [[Rotating Savings and Credit Association|rotating savings and credit association]] (ROSCA), tontines are well established as a savings instrument in central Africa, and in this case function as savings clubs in which each member makes regular payments and is lent the [[wiktionary:kitty#noun|kitty]] in turn. They are wound up after each cycle of loans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ecole.org/seminaires/FS3/SEM105/VC190603-ENG.pdf |title=Using tontines to run the economy |first=Alain |last=Henry |publisher=l'\u00c9cole de Paris du management |date=June 19, 2003}}</ref> In West Africa, \"tontines\" \u2013 often consisting of mainly women \u2013 are an example of economic, social and cultural solidarity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dandc.eu/en/article/self-organised-savings-communities-tontines-are-example-economic-social-and-cultural |title=Flexible and disciplined |first=Eva-Maria |last=Bruchhaus |publisher=D+C, Development and Cooperation |date=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nInformal group savings and loan associations are also traditional in many east Asian societies, and under the name of tontines are found in [[Cambodia]], and among emigrant Cambodian communities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cambodia.org.nz/Tontine.htm |title=Tontine: an alternative financial instrument in Cambodian communities |first=Man Hau |last=Liev |publisher=12th NZASIA Conference |date=November 26\u201329, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Singapore]], the Chit Funds Act of 1971<ref>{{cite web |title=Chit Funds Act |work=Singapore Statutes Online |origyear=1971 |year=2013 |url=https://sso.agc.gov.sg/Act/CFA1971 |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref> defines the application of legislation to the operation of [[chit fund]]s, which were also known colloquially as tontines but which operated on a different principle more commonly known as a ROSCA ([[Rotating Savings and Credit Association]]).\n \nIn [[Malaysia]], chit funds are primarily known as \"kootu funds\", which again are ROSCAs and which are defined under the ''Kootu Funds (Prohibition) Act 1971'' as \n\"...a scheme or arrangement variously known as a kootu, cheetu, chit fund, hwei, tontine or otherwise whereby the participants subscribe periodically or otherwise to a common fund and such common fund is put up for sale or payment to the participants by auction, tender, bid, ballot or otherwise...\" <ref>{{cite web |title=Kootu Funds (Prohibition) Act 1971 |work=Commonwealth Legal Information Institute |year=1971 |url=http://www.commonlii.org/my/legis/consol_act/kfa1971281/ |accessdate=27 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nTontines have been featured as plot devices in many fictional stories, movies and television programs, including:\n*''La Tontine'' (1708), a comic play by [[Alain-Ren\u00e9 Lesage]]. A physician, hoping to raise the funds to give his daughter a dowry, buys a tontine on the life of an elderly peasant, who he then strives to keep alive.\n*''The Great Tontine'' (1881), is a novel by [[Henry Hawley Smart|Hawley Smart]].\n*''[[The Wrong Box (novel)|The Wrong Box]]'' (1889), is a comic novel by [[Robert Louis Stevenson]] and [[Lloyd Osbourne]]. The plot revolves around a tontine originally taken out for some wealthy English children, and the resulting shenanigans as younger family members of the two final survivors vie to secure the final payout. The book was adapted as a [[The Wrong Box|film]], produced and directed by [[Bryan Forbes]], (1966).\n*''The Secret Tontine'' (1912), is an atmospheric faux-gothic novel by [[Robert Murray Gilchrist]], set in the [[Derbyshire]] [[Peak District]] during a snowy winter in the late 19th century. The plot involves the potential beneficiaries of a covert tontine, and their scheme to murder their ignorant rivals. \n*[[Lillian de la Torre]]'s short story \"The Tontine Curse\" (1948) features mysterious deaths related to a tontine in 1779, being investigated by [[Samuel Johnson]].\n*''The Tontine'' (1955), a novel by [[Thomas B. Costain]], illustrated by [[Herbert Ryman]], is set in nineteenth-century England and tells a story centered around the fictional \"Waterloo Tontine\", established to benefit veterans of the Napoleonic wars. Among other plot twists, shareholders hire an actor to impersonate a dead nominee, and conspire to murder another member.\n*In ''[[4.50 from Paddington]]'' (1957), a [[Miss Marple]] murder mystery by [[Agatha Christie]], the plot revolves around the will of a wealthy industrialist, which establishes a [[Settlement (trust)|settlement]] under which his estate is divided in trust among his grandchildren, the final survivor to inherit the whole. The settlement is described, inaccurately, as a tontine. \n*''[[Something Fishy]]'' (1957), a novel by [[P. G. Wodehouse]], features a so-called tontine under which the investors' sons stand to gain from marrying late.\n* In the U.S. television series ''[[The Wild Wild West]]'', Episode 16 of Season Two (1966\u201367) \u2013 \"The Night of the Tottering Tontine\" \u2013 finds James West and Artemus Gordon protecting a man who is a member of a tontine whose members are being murdered one by another.\n*\"Old Soldiers,\" an eighth-season episode of the television series ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'', focuses on a tontine set up among Colonel Potter and several of his Army buddies from [[World War I]]. While taking shelter in a ch\u00e2teau during an artillery barrage, they had found a cache of brandy and drank all but one bottle, which they set aside for the last survivor. After the only other surviving member dies, Potter receives the bottle in the mail and shares it with his staff, drinking first to his departed friends and then to the new ones he has made at the 4077th.\n*In the ''[[Barney Miller]]'' episode \"The Tontine\" (1982), one of the last two surviving family members who invested in the tontine attempts to kill himself so that the other can have the money before growing too old to enjoy it.\n* In ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Raging Abe Simpson and His Grumbling Grandson in \"The Curse of the Flying Hellfish\"]]\" (1996), [[Grampa Simpson]] and [[Mr. Burns]] are the final survivors of a tontine to determine ownership of art looted during [[World War II]]. Grampa eventually kicks Burns out of the tontine for trying to kill him, but before he and Bart can do anything with the art, a descendant of the original owner shows up to claim it.\n*In [[S. L. Viehl]]'s science fiction multi-volume novel ''Stardoc'' (2000), the title character is accused of spreading a plague to several colony worlds, on one of which the colonists had established a tontine. The sole survivor, a little girl, consequently becomes so wealthy that in the second book of the series \u2013 ''Beyond Varallan'' (2000) \u2013 she buys the bank behind the colonies to free the Stardoc from the debt she now owes.\n*The 2001 comedy film ''[[Tomcats (2001 film)|Tomcats]]'' features a variation on a tontine where the last investor to get married gets the full amount of the invested funds.\n* In the ''[[Archer (2009 TV series)|Archer]]'' episode \"The Double Deuce\" (2011), Archer's [[valet]] Woodhouse is revealed as one of three final survivors of a group of World War I [[Royal Flying Corps]] squadron mates who each put [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]50 into an interest-bearing account, now worth nearly a million [[United States dollar|dollars]]. The office workers at ISIS HQ, realizing that a new tontine could capitalize on the high mortality rate of field agents, begin persuading people to join.\n* The ''[[Diagnosis: Murder]]'' episode \"Being of Sound Mind\" (Season 8 Episode 16) features a tontine as a motive for murder.\n*The ''[[The Brokenwood Mysteries|Brokenwood Mysteries]]'' episode \"Tontine\" (Season 5 Episode 3) centres on a tontine.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last=Buley|first=R. Carlyle|title=The Equitable Life Assurance Society of the United States 1859\u20131964|date=1967|publisher=Appleton-Century-Crofts|location=New York}}\n*{{cite book |first=Geoffrey |last=Clark |title=Betting on Lives: the culture of life insurance in England, 1695\u20131775 |location=Manchester |publisher=Manchester University Press |year=1999 |isbn=9780719056758 }} \n*{{Cite journal |first=Julien |last=Coudy |title=La Tontine royal sous le r\u00e8gne de Louis XIV |journal=Revue historique de droit fran\u00e7ais et \u00e9tranger |volume=4th ser. 35 |year=1957 |pages=128\u201333 |language=fr}}\n*{{Cite journal |first=John |last=Dunkley |title=Bourbons on the Rocks: tontines and early public lotteries in France |journal=Journal for Eighteenth-Century Studies |volume=30 |issue=3 |year=2007 |pages=309\u201323 |doi=10.1111/j.1754-0208.2007.tb00338.x}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Gallais Hamonno |first1=Georges |last2=Berthon |first2=Jean |title=Les emprunts tontiniers de l'Ancien R\u00e9gime: un exemple d'ing\u00e9nierie financi\u00e8re au XVIIIe si\u00e8cle |location=Paris |year=2008 |language=fr}}\n*{{cite journal|first=David R. |last=Green |title=Tontines, annuities and civic improvements in Georgian Britain |journal=Urban History |volume=46 |issue=4 |year=2019 |pages=649\u201394 |doi=10.1017/s0963926818000743 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last1=Jennings |first1=Robert M. |last2=Trout |first2=Andrew P. |title=The Tontine: fact and fiction |journal=Journal of European Economic History |volume=5 |year=1976 |pages=663\u201370 }}\n*{{Cite book |last1=Jennings |first1=Robert M. |last2=Trout |first2=Andrew P. |title=The Tontine: from the reign of Louis XIV to the French Revolutionary era |location=Homewood, IL |year=1982 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last1=Jennings |first1=Robert M. |last2=Swanson |first2=Donald F. |last3=Trout |first3=Andrew P. |title=Alexander Hamilton's tontine proposal |journal=William and Mary Quarterly |series=3rd ser. |volume=45 |issue=1 |year=1988 |pages=107\u2013115 |jstor=1922216|doi=10.2307/1922216 }}\n*{{Cite journal |url=http://ir.lawnet.fordham.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1108&context=jcfl&sei-redir=1#search=%22fordham%20tontines%22 |first=Kent |last=McKeever |title=A Short History of Tontines |journal=[[Fordham Journal of Corporate & Financial Law]] |volume=15 |issue=2 |year=2011 |pages=491\u2013521}}\n*{{cite book |last=Milevsky |first=Moshe A. |authorlink=Moshe Milevsky |title=King William's Tontine: why the retirement annuity of the future should resemble its past |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |year=2015 |isbn=978-110-707612-9}}\n*{{Cite journal |first=David R. |last=Weir |title=Tontines, Public Finance, and Revolution in France and England, 1688\u20131789 |journal=Journal of Economic History |volume=49 |year=1989 |pages=95\u2013124 |doi=10.1017/s002205070000735x|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/6b6216730f9bb206697414ac38327061feb3673d }}\n*{{Cite book|author=Wyler, Julius |title=Die Tontinen in Frankreich |location=Munich and Leipzig |year=1916 |language=de}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|tontine}}\n*[[wikisource:The Story of Life Insurance/Chapter IV|\"The Great Tontine Gamble\"]], one of a series of articles by [[Burton J. Hendrick]] appearing in ''[[McClure's Magazine]]'' in 1906\n*[http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a3_172.html ''The Straight Dope'': \"What's with tontines, the odd annuities in which you benefit when others die?\"]\n*[http://www.cato.org/pubs/regulation/regv32n4/v32n4-4.pdf Baker et al. (Winter 2009-2010) \"Tontines for the Young Invincibles\", ''Regulation'']\n*[https://www.forbes.com/sites/pensionresearchcouncil/2018/01/30/fintechs-answer-to-the-global-retirement-crisis/#586b0cd31ff3 \"Forbes  Pensions Research Council (Jan 18, 2018) \"Fintech's Answer To The Global Retirement Crisis\"]\n\n{{Economic history of the Netherlands}}\n\n[[Category:Investment]]\n[[Category:Informal finance]]\n[[Category:1653 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:17th-century introductions]]\n[[Category:Economic history of the Netherlands]]\n", "name_user": "GrindtXX", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix citation etc (inc punct before ref; straight quotes)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tontine"}
{"title_page": "Melita issue", "text_new": "{{multiple image|perrow = 3 |total_width=550\n| image1 = Malta 1922 Melita 1d orange & purple.jpg |width1=643|height1=779\n| image2 = Malta 1922 Melita 1s indigo & sepia.jpg |width2=643|height2=779\n| image3 = Malta 1922 Melita \u00a31 black & carmine-red.jpg |width3=643 |height3=779\n| footer = The different designs used in the Melita issue: [[Penny|pence]] values designed by [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] (left), [[shilling]] values by [[Gianni Vella]] (centre) and [[Pound sterling|pound]] value by Caruana Dingli (right){{efn|There are minor design differences between the pence and pound values which are both based on Caruana Dingli's design, including the shape of the value tablet and the typeface used for the country name.}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Melita issue''' is a series of dual-purpose [[Postage stamp|postage]]-and-[[Revenue stamp|revenue stamps]] issued by the [[Crown Colony of Malta]] between 1922 and 1926, depicting the national personification [[Melita (personification)|Melita]]. They were [[commemorative stamp]]s since they celebrated the islands' new status as a [[self-governing colony]] following a new constitution in 1921, but also a [[Definitive stamp|definitive issue]] intended for regular use over an extended period of time.\n\nDesigned by two leading Maltese artists, [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] and [[Gianni Vella]], the issue consisted of stamps in various denominations from \u00bc[[pence|d]] to [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]1; Caruana Dingli's designs were used on the pence and pound values and Vella's design on the shilling values. The designs were poorly received when they were issued, and Caruana Dingli himself criticized the execution of the design. In subsequent years, however, Caruana Dingli's design came to be regarded as one of the most iconic Malta stamps, and his design for the figure of Melita formed the basis of the [[Maltese lira]] banknotes of 1989\u20132008 and gold [[bullion coin]]s minted since 2018.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Malta 1899 Melita 2s6d olive-grey.jpg|thumb|left|The 1899 Melita stamp]]\n\nThe oldest known depiction of a personification of Malta dates back to 1481. The figure of [[Melita (personification)|Melita]] seems to have developed from allegorical representations of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St John]], which [[History of Malta under the Order of Saint John|ruled Malta]] between 1530 and 1798.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kinnane-Roelofsma |first1=Derk |title=Britannia and Melita: Pseudomorphic Sisters |journal=Journal of the Warbourg and Courtauld Insitute |date=1996 |volume=59 |pages=130\u2013147}}</ref>\n\nMelita first appeared on stamps in 1899. A 2[[shilling|s]]/6d olive-grey stamp depicted her holding a sword and a shield, the latter emblazoned with the [[Maltese cross]]. In the background were the flags of Malta and of the Order.<ref>{{cite web |title=The \"Melita\" Stamp of Malta |url=https://www.mintageworld.com/media/detail/7401-the-melita-stamp-of-malta/ |website=Mintage World |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122142635/https://www.mintageworld.com/media/detail/7401-the-melita-stamp-of-malta/ |archivedate=22 January 2019 |date=21 August 2018}}</ref> This stamp was reissued with a different [[watermark]] in 1919, and remained in use until it was replaced by the 1922 Melita issue.<ref name=\"sg\">{{cite book |title=Stanley Gibbons Stamp Catalogue: Commonwealth and British Empire Stamps 1840\u20131970 |date=2015 |publisher=[[Stanley Gibbons]] |location=London |isbn=978-0-85259-918-1 |pages=401\u2013402 |edition=117}}</ref> Special printings of the 1899 design, sometimes in new colours or watermarks, were also issued with [[overprint]]s for [[Revenue stamps of Malta|revenue purposes]] between 1902 and 1908.<ref name=\"mcclellan\"/>\n\nIn 1921, the British [[Crown Colony of Malta]] was granted a limited form of [[self-governing colony|self-government]] according to the Amery-Milner Constitution. This divided control of Malta between two governments: the Maltese Government and the Maltese Imperial Government. The former included a [[Bicameralism|bicameral legislature]] with a [[Senate of Malta|Senate]] and [[Parliament of Malta|Legislative Assembly]], while the Imperial Government was led by the [[List of Governors of Malta|Governor of Malta]], a British colonial official who retained direct responsibility of certain reserved matters such as defence and maintaining public order.<ref name=\"bephila\">{{cite web|title=Melita Issue of Malta Stamps: 1922\u201326|url=http://www.bephila.com/articles/melita-issue-of-malta-stamps-1922-26|website=British Empire Philately|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316113650/http://www.bephila.com/articles/melita-issue-of-malta-stamps-1922-26|archivedate=16 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Cassar |first1=Carmel |title=A Concise History of Malta |date=2000 |publisher=Mireva Publications |location=[[Msida]] |isbn=1870579526 |page=204}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June 1921, a [[design competition|competition]] was announced calling for the design of a set of stamps to commemorate Malta's partial independence. The stamps were therefore to be [[commemorative stamp|commemoratives]], but they were also intended as [[Definitive stamp|definitives]] for regular use over an extended period of time.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nThe Maltese wanted to issue the new stamps by the time the new parliament was inaugurated on 1 November 1921. There was not enough time for the stamps to be produced and delivered within that timeframe, however, since the printers [[De La Rue]] had to deal with a large workload, causing delays. The Malta Post Office therefore decided to overprint the then-current definitives (which depicted King [[George V]] and some pictorial scenes, including the 1919 reprint of the 1899 Melita design) with the words \"SELF-GOVERNMENT\" diagonally to commemorate the new constitution.<ref name=\"bephila\"/> The overprinting was carried out by the Government Printing Office in the capital [[Valletta]], and the stamps were released between 12 January and 29 April 1922.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\n==Design==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 320\n | image_style = border:none;\n | image1 = Malta -mix- 2019 by-RaBoe 260.jpg\n | alt1 = A lighthouse\n | image2 = Gozo boat cropped.jpg\n | alt2 = Painting of a boat\n | footer = The St Elmo lighthouse and a [[Gozo boat]] (painting pictured) are depicted in the background of Caruana Dingli's design\n}}\n\nTwo designs were chosen from the competition, one by [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] and one by [[Gianni Vella]]. Caruana Dingli's design was used for ten denominations: the [[Penny|pence]] values ranging from \u00bcd to 6d, and also the highest value of the set, the [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1. Vella's design was used for the five [[shilling]] values ranging from 1/- to 10/-.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nCaruana Dingli's design depicts [[Melita (personification)|Melita]] as a robed and helmeted figure holding a [[rudder]], representing Malta as being in control of her own destiny.<ref name=\"cbm-bullion\"/> The background contains a seascape, with the lighthouse near [[Fort Saint Elmo]] and a [[Gozo boat]] visible. Shields depicting the [[Union Jack]] and a colonial badge representing Malta are located at the bottom of the design.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nVella's design contains two figures representing Malta and the United Kingdom, Melita and [[Brittania]]. Melita holds an olive branch in her hand, and embraces Brittania by lifting her hand around Brittania's neck. Brittania wears a helmet and holds a shield with the Union Jack. The figure representing the United Kingdom is sometimes interpreted as being a male figure,<ref name=\"bephila\"/><ref name=\"times20111204\">{{cite news |last1=Bonavia |first1=Carmel |title=Stamps marking Malta's constitutional development |url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20111204/life-features/Stamps-marking-Malta-s-constitutional-development.397019 |work=[[Times of Malta]] |date=4 December 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911114312/https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20111204/life-features/Stamps-marking-Malta-s-constitutional-development.397019 |archivedate=11 September 2018}}</ref> but was intended as female, with the design representing Malta and Britain as sisters or mother and daughter.<ref name=\"linns\"/><ref name=\"bop1922\"/> This represented the care and protection that Britain offered Malta, and symbolized friendly relations between them. This design also contains the Roman numerals MCMXXI (1921) to the left of the figures. The Maltese emblem is located at the lower left corner, while many small Maltese crosses frame the design.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\n[[File:Malta 1922 Melita 1d orange &amp; purple postally and fiscally used.jpg|thumb|300px|Examples of the 1d orange and purple postally used (strip of three with [[Sliema]] postmarks) and fiscally used (single with an [[Anglo-Egyptian Bank]] cancellation)]]\n\nBoth designs contain the inscription \"POSTAGE [&] REVENUE\", indicating that they were valid for use as both [[postage stamp]]s and [[revenue stamp]]s. They can therefore be found both postally and fiscally used.<ref name=\"mcclellan\">{{cite web|last1=McClellan|first1=Andrew|title=Malta|url=http://www.revrevd.com/malta.html|website=Revenue Reverend|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924105952/http://www.revrevd.com/malta.html|archivedate=24 September 2017|date=2011\u201317}}</ref>\n\n==Technical details==\n[[File:Watermark crown script CA.jpg|thumb|left|The Multiple Script CA watermark]]\n\nThe stamps of the Melita issue were printed by De La Rue using typography, with the exception of the \u00a31 top value which was [[Intaglio (printmaking)|recess-printed]]. The typographed stamps were printed on chalk-surfaced paper. Each stamp was printed in two operations, with a [[Key type stamp|key plate and a duty plate]]. In most cases each plate was printed in a different colour, but for some of the low values both plates were printed in the same colour.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nThe [[watermark]] used on the stamps is known as ''Multiple Script CA'', since it consists of the letters \"CA\" (referring to the [[Crown Agents]]) in a script typeface, beneath a representation of the [[Tudor Crown (heraldry)|Tudor crown]], arranged multiple times next to each other. The watermark was sideways for the pence values and upright for the shilling values. The \u00a31 was initially printed with an upright watermark but in 1925 it was also issued with a sideways watermark.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nThe pence values were printed in sheets of 160 stamps (consisting of two panes, each containing 8 rows of 10 stamps, separated by a [[Gutter (philately)|gutter]]), the shilling values were printed in sheets of 80 (one pane of 8 rows of 10 stamps) and the \u00a31 value was printed in sheets of 40 (one pane of 4 rows of 10 stamps).<ref name=\"bephila\"/> The stamps were perforated with [[Perforation gauge|gauge]] 14.2 by 14 comb perforations.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nA number of [[Die proof (philately)|die proofs]] and plate proofs of stamps from the Melita issue exist. Die proofs are individual prints from the stamps' original [[Die (philately)|die]]s made at various stages of production, and are impressions of either the key die or the duty die of each value, or composite die proofs of both dies together. Plate proofs, which are test printings made from the stamps' printings plates, exist of the \u00bcd, \u00bdd, 1d, 3d and \u00a31 values in unissued colours. A wide range of versions of these exist, either perforated or imperforate, on unwatermarked or watermarked paper, and with or without a [[Specimen stamp|specimen overprint]]. Specimens of all the stamps in the issued colours also exist, except for the reprints made in slightly different shades, the 1925 2\u00bdd on 3d surcharge, and the 1926 postage overprints.<ref name=\"trory\"/>\n\n==Issued stamps==\n[[File:Malta 1925 Melita 2\u00bdd on 3d bright ultramarine.jpg|thumb|The 1925 2\u00bdd on 3d surcharge]]\n\nThe first Melita stamps were issued on 1 August 1922, with the denominations of \u00bdd, 1d, 6d, 1/- and 2/-. A \u00bcd value was issued on 22 August, followed by 2d, 3d, 4d, 2/6, 5/-, 10/- and \u00a31 values on 28 August. A 1\u00bdd value was added on 1 October 1923. On 25 April 1924, the 1d value was reissued in a new colour while the \u00bcd and 3d were reissued in slightly different shades.<ref name=\"jb\">{{cite book |last1=Buttigieg |first1=Joseph |title=The JB Catalogue of Malta Stamps and Postal History |date=2014 |publisher=Sliema Stamp Shop |location=[[Sliema]] |pages=10\u201311 |edition=22}}</ref> The \u00a31 was reissued in a slightly different shade and with a different orientation of the watermark on 14 May 1925.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\nA requirement for a 2\u00bdd value arose when the foreign-letter rate was reduced in 1925;<ref name=\"gps74\">{{cite journal |last1=Poulton |first1=Mark Anthony |title=The Gozo Boat on Malta Stamps |journal=Gozo Philatelic Society Newlsetter |date=2018 |issue=74 |pages=6\u201313 |url=https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar/handle/123456789/37744}}</ref> stocks of the 3d were overprinted \"Two pence halfpenny\" by the Government Printing Office and were issued on 3 December 1925. A 2\u00bdd value and the 3d in a new colour were subsequently issued on 16 February 1926.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Denomination\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" style =\"width:18%\" | Colour 1\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" style =\"width:18%\" | Colour 2\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" | Paper \n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" style =\"width:8%\" | Watermark orientation\n! scope=\"col\" | Date of issue\n|-\n| {{sort|000.25|\u00bcd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#773b31\" | brown || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-22|22 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|000.25|\u00bcd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#773b31\" | chocolate-brown || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1924-04-25|25 April 1924}}\n|- \n| {{sort|000.50|\u00bdd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#477159\" | green || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|001.00|1d}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#f67c36\" | orange || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#a33550\" | purple || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|001.00|1d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#894c78\" | bright violet || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1924-04-25|25 April 1924}}\n|- \n| {{sort|001.50|1\u00bdd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#a73422\" | brown-red || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1923-10-01|1 October 1923}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.00|2d}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#895732\" | bistre-brown || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#61beaa\" | turquoise || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.50|2\u00bdd on 3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#606fa8\" | cobalt || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1925-12-03|3 December 1925}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.50|2\u00bdd on 3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#476eb9\" | bright ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1925-12-09|9 December 1925}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.50|2\u00bdd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#476eb9\" | ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1926-02-16|16 February 1926}}\n|- \n| {{sort|003.00|3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#606fa8\" | cobalt || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|003.00|3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#476eb9\" | bright ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1924-04-25|25 April 1924}}\n|- \n| {{sort|003.00|3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#4a4742\" | black || bgcolor=\"#e6d649\" | yellow, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1926-02-16|16 February 1926}}\n|- \n| {{sort|004.00|4d}} || bgcolor=\"#febe2f\" | yellow || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#4c5b92\" | bright blue || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|006.00|6d}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#77743f\" | olive-green || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#5f3364\" | reddish violet || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|012.00|1/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#26486D\" | indigo || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#78462d\" | sepia || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|024.00|2/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#744028\" | brown || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#4c62a1\" | blue || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|030.00|2/6}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#9a427e\" | bright magenta || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#272528\" | black || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|060.00|5/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#c9672a\" | orange-yellow || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#384999\" | bright ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|120.00|10/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#837873\" | slate-grey || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#7c4d36\" | brown || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|240.00|\u00a31}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#211f22\" | black || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#b32026\" | carmine-red || white, ordinary || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|240.00|\u00a31}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#211f22\" | black || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#b32026\" | bright carmine || white, ordinary || sideways || {{sort|1925-05-14|14 May 1925}}\n|- \n|}\n\nSome stamps exist with an inverted watermark, and flaws are known on the 1d and 3d values.<ref name=\"trory\">{{cite book |title=The John A. Trory Specialised Catalogue of Malta |date=1990 |page=20 |edition=6}}</ref>\n\n==1926 Postage overprints==\n[[File:Malta 1926 Melita Postage 1\u00bdd brown-red.jpg|thumb|The 1\u00bdd with the \"POSTAGE\" overprint]]\n\nDue to a change in procedure, dual-purpose postage-and-revenue stamps were discontinued in 1926 and replaced by separate issues of postage stamps and revenue stamps,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Smeed|first1=Graham|title=Malta Revenue Stamps|date=1977|publisher=Malta Study Circle|page=5}}</ref> so it was decided to overprint the stamps of the Melita issue with the word \"POSTAGE\". The [[Forme (printing)|forme]] of the overprint was prepared by John Muscat Fenech and Carmelo Cacopardo, and the overprinting was hastily carried out by the Government Printing Office on a Warfedale printing press in the last week of March 1926. The ink used in the overprinting was a special mix made at the Office of Public Health.<ref name=\"invert\"/> The overprinting was applied to all the stamps from \u00bcd to 10/-, except those which had been earlier replaced by new colours, and the stamps were issued on 1 April 1926.<ref name=\"sg\"/> The overprints were on sale for only about a week, and a new series of stamps bearing the \"POSTAGE\" inscription was issued only five days later on 6 April.<ref name=\"sg\"/><ref name=\"gsm2019\">{{cite magazine |last1=Davenhill |first1=Noel |title=British Colonial and Protectorate Stamps \u2013 Part 19: Malta |magazine=[[Gibbons Stamp Monthly]] |date=December 2019 |volume=50 |issue=7 |pages=62\u201368 |publisher=Stanley Gibbons Ltd}}</ref>\n\nSome stamps with had errors were detected during the printing, and these were kept by the Acting Postmaster General before being burnt at the Power Station. Despite this, some stamps with errors still ended up in circulation, including the 3d value with the overprint inverted, and various denominations with the overprints misplaced to varying degrees, the most notable being a variety of the 4d in which the overprint reads \"AGE POST\".<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\n===3d with inverted overprint===\n[[File:Malta 1926 Melita Postage 3d black on yellow overprint inverted.jpg|thumb|The 3d with the \"POSTAGE\" overprint inverted]]\n\nThe 3d black on yellow is known with the [[Invert error|overprint inverted]], and it is one of Malta's best-known error stamps. It is believed that only two sheets of the error were printed, and they were allegedly acquired on the first day of issue by Alfredo Caruana Gatto, a [[Maltese Political Union]] politician who was a member of the Senate and who had been Minister for Justice in 1921\u201322. The exact circumstances of their issue remain unclear, and it is not known whether they were acquired over the Post Office counter or not. Caruana Gatto is said to have immediately sold the two sheets to Carol Saliba and Pio Grech, and the sheets were eventually broken down and sold to stamp dealers and collectors. A small amount of the error stamps were used on mail by philatelists, but the vast majority were retained in [[Mint stamp|mint condition]].<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\nIn 1930, uncertainty about the stamp's issue formed the basis of a political campaign by the [[Constitutional Party (Malta)|Constitutional Party]] against the [[Nationalist Party (Malta)|Nationalist Party]] which became known as the \"Postage Stamps Scandal\". The matter was brought up in the Legislative Assembly on 31 March 1930 when Constitutional Party member Alfred Gera De Petri asked Robert Hamilton, the Minister for Posts, about the circumstances of the stamp's issue. A committee was later appointed to investigate the matter, and it included [[Gerald Strickland, 1st Baron Strickland|Gerald Strickland]], Hamilton, Walter Salomone, [[Paul Boffa]] and [[Ugo Pasquale Mifsud]].<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\nThe committee members belonging to the Constitutional Party produced a report in which they stated that there was no evidence that the error was ever sold at a Post Office or that Caruana Gatto (who had died in 1926) had sold the stamps. They concluded that the inverted overprint was applied at the Government Printing Office without authorisation to sheets of genuine stamps which were not part of the Post Office stock, meaning that the overprints were forged. Boffa mentioned that the overprinting might have even been done outside the Government Printing Office, while Mifsud only agreed with the conclusion that there was no evidence of Caruana Gatto's involvement in the matter. There were gaps in the evidence collected by the committee, and it did not produce any arguments which countered various opinions that the overprints were the result of a genuine mistake, making its findings inconclusive. The committee's report was criticized in the press.<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\nPhilatelists regard the inverted overprint as a genuine error,<ref name=\"sg\"/> even though its exact origins remain unknown.<ref name=\"invert\">{{cite journal |last1=Ganado |first1=Albert |title=The Melita 3d. Postage Inverted: Politics embroil philately |journal=Melita Historica |date=2007 |volume=XIV |issue=4 |pages=409\u2013428 |url=http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Melita%20Historica/MH.14(2004-07)/MH.14(2007)4/04.pdf |issn=1021-6952|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121232400/http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Melita%20Historica/MH.14(2004-07)/MH.14(2007)4/04.pdf|archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe stamps received mostly negative reactions from the public and stamp collectors upon their release. Even Caruana Dingli was dissatisfied with the way the stamps were printed, stating in the local newspaper ''Il Popolo di Malta'' on 4 August 1922 that:<ref name=\"times20111204\"/>\n{{cquote|After correcting the first proofs and suggesting certain artistic retouching, I regret to say, that the result still fell short of my expectations. My original was copied by hand and alterations were introduced resulting in a totally different effect from that originally intended.|20px}}\nAmongst other criticism, he expressed his dissatisfaction that the lighthouse in the background was remodelled to look like a [[beehive]] or the [[Rotunda of Mosta|Mosta Dome]]. He also complained that the colours were not to his liking, and that he had not been consulted about them. He exhibited an enlarged version of his original design at the [[National Library of Malta|Bibliotheca]] in Valletta to showcase the difference in the designs.<ref name=\"times20111204\"/>\n\n[[File:Malta 1922 Melita 4d yellow &amp; bright blue.jpg|thumb|left|The colour scheme of the 4d was criticized when the stamps were issued]]\n\nAn article in ''[[The Boy's Own Paper]]'' described the issue as a \"handsome set\", but also mentioned the criticism aimed at the colour scheme of the 4d value in yellow and blue. This article incorrectly identified Melita as being a [[Nereid|sea nymph]].<ref name=\"bop1922\">{{cite book |title=The Boy's Own Paper |date=1922 |publisher=Leisure Hour Office |pages=227\u2013228 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IsPnAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA227#v=onepage&q&f=false |volume=45 |chapter=The \"B.O.P.\" Stamp Corner}}</ref> In ''Mekeel's Weekly Stamp News'' of 16 May 1927, a certain Capt. H. W. Jessop wrote that:<ref name=\"linns\">{{cite web |title=Malta's 1922 Melita issue: Fine art or poorly done stamps? |url=https://www.linns.com/news/us-stamps-postal-history/2017/january/malta-melita-stamp-issue-fine-art-poorly-done.html |website=[[Linn's Stamp News]] |date=1 January 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/75cWftBrr|archivedate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n{{cquote|though not in themselves displeasing, [the stamps] did not meet with a very enthusiastic reception either from the general public or from collectors.|20px}}\nCriticism was also directed towards the lack of a portrait of King [[George V]] on the stamps, although the stamps were aimed at specifically manifesting Malta's newly established freedom from total British control.<ref name=\"linns\"/>\n\nThe 1926 Postage overprints were widely criticized as being unnecessary,<ref name=\"gsm2019\"/> and they were unpopular both locally and among collectors.<ref name=\"gps74\"/>\n\nIn contrast to when it was issued, today Caruana Dingli's design is held in high esteem, and in 2011 [[MaltaPost]] stated that \"it is widely considered to be one of Malta's most beautiful stamps.\"<ref name=\"maltapost2011\"/> A 2019 article in the ''Stamp Magazine'' describes the Melita issue as \"some of Malta's finest\" stamp designs, but also comments on the contrast between Caruana Dingli's and Vella's Melitas, describing the latter as having \"an awkward pose\".<ref name=\"stampmagazine2019\">{{cite magazine |last1=Winchester |first1=John |title=The odd couple |magazine=Stamp Magazine |date=February 2019 |volume=85 |issue=2 |page=51}}</ref>\n\n==Sale and collecting==\nIn 1922\u201323 the Post Office recorded an increase of \u00a31920. 19s. 9\u00bdd. in revenue when compared to the previous year.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1922 |date=1923 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108153623/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref> This increase was attributed to the sale of stamps to [[philately|philatelists]] \"owing to the issue of new design stamps\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1924 |date=1925 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1924/1924_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108154434/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1924/1924_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref>{{efn|The statistics in the 1922 Blue Book are for the period lasting from 1 April 1922 to 31 March 1923.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1922 |date=1923 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section2.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108153618/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section2.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Abstract of the Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref> The only new stamps issued during this period were a \u00bcd surcharged stamp on 15 April, 6d and \u00bdd Self-Government overprints on 19 and 24 April respectively, and the Melita issue between 1 and 28 August. The Melita issue was the only issue with a new design.<ref name=\"sg\"/>}} A massive increase of \u00a327977. 16s. 6\u00bdd.  in Post Office revenue was registered in 1925\u201326 when compared to 1924\u201325, and this was attributed to \"an abnormal quantity of stamps sold to collectors for philatelic purposes\" along with increased use of stamps for postal purposes.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1926 |date=1927 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108155457/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref>{{efn|The statistics in the 1926 Blue Book are for the period lasting from 1 April 1925 to 31 March 1926.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1926 |date=1927 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section2.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108155453/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section2.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Abstract of the Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref> The only new postage stamps issued during this period were all from the Melita issue: the reprint of the \u00a31 on 14 May 1925, the 2\u00bdd on 3d surcharge in December 1925, and the 2\u00bdd and 3d in new colours on 16 February 1926. In addition, there were two new sets of [[postage due]] stamps issued on 16 April and 20 July 1925.<ref name=\"sg\"/>}} In 1926\u201327, another massive increase of \u00a324870. 8s. 2d. was attributed to \"large sales of stamps overprinted \"Postage\".\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1927 |date=1928 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1927/1927_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108160038/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1927/1927_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref>\n\nDue to the criticism at the colour scheme of the 4d value, that stamp was reportedly withdrawn by the postal authorities soon after it was issued. Some believed that the stamp could become a rarity and examples of it were sold for as much as 30/-. After a couple of days the stamp once again became available at post offices,<ref name=\"bop1922\"/> and it is no longer scarcer than the other stamps in the issue.<ref name=\"sg\"/> Today, the 1922\u201326 stamps are not rare, and the lower values up to the 2/6 are relatively cheap. The higher values are more expensive,<ref name=\"stampmagazine2019\"/> with the most valuable stamp being the original \u00a31 value of 1922 with a sideways watermark.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\n[[File:Malta 1930 AR cover to United States.jpg|thumb|1\u00bdd and 3d Melita stamps with the \"POSTAGE\" overprint used on a 1930 registered cover to the United States. The cover was sent by Rupert Forbes-Bentley, a stamp dealer.<ref name=\"invert\"/>]]\n\nAlthough the 1926 Postage overprints were only on sale for about one week, the bulk of the stamps were sold to stamp dealers and collectors so most of them remain common. However, some values sold out soon after they were issued<ref name=\"gps74\"/> and stamps with the denominations of 4d, 2/-, 2/6 and 5/- are quite expensive today. Since they were only in use briefly, most of the 1926 overprints are more valuable in used condition.<ref name=\"sg\"/> The \"POSTAGE\" overprint has also been [[Philatelic fakes and forgeries|forged]], particularly on the 2/- and 2/6 denominations and on the 3d with inverted overprint.<ref name=\"trory\"/>\n\nThe Malta Study Circle, a group of philatelists who study Malta's stamps and postal history, has produced a number of publications relating to the Melita issue. Two study papers which related to the original 1922\u201326 issue and the 1926 Postage overprints were published in 1970,<ref>{{cite web |title=Melita 1922\u20131926 |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?revHistory=24&category=0 |website=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415112251/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?revHistory=24&category=0 |archivedate=15 April 2020}}</ref> and they were combined into a single paper in 1972. A rewritten paper was published in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=Study Papers |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?pageInfo=2&thisPageSize=20 |website=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415112254/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?pageInfo=2&thisPageSize=20 |archivedate=15 April 2020}}</ref> The Study Circle's newsletter which is published three times a year is also entitled ''Melita''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/about/information.asp |website=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415112257/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/about/information.asp |archivedate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nAn allegorical figure with a pose similar to Caruana Dingli's Melita design was used on the fifth and final series of [[Maltese lira]] banknotes. These banknotes were introduced by the [[Central Bank of Malta]] on 18 September 1989, coinciding with the 25th anniversary of independence, and they had four denominations: Lm2, Lm5, Lm10 and Lm20. Another series of banknotes with the same design but with amended security features was issued on 1 June 1994. Versions with signatures of different Governors of the Central Bank were issued in 1997, 1999 and 2001, and there was also a special issue for collectors in 2000.<ref>{{cite book |title=Said Malta Coin & Banknote Catalogue 2010 |date=2010 |publisher=Said International Ltd |pages=180\u2013193}}</ref> These banknotes remained in use until Malta adopted the [[euro]] on 1 January 2008, and remained legal tender until 31 January 2008; they were demonetized ten years later on 31 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maltese banknotes \u2013 5th Series and enhanced version (not legal tender after 31 January 2008)|url=http://www.centralbankmalta.org/site/currency2e.html|publisher=[[Central Bank of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227162525/http://www.centralbankmalta.org/site/currency2e.html|archivedate=27 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Timeline Banknotes |url=https://www.centralbankmalta.org/timeline-banknotes |website=[[Central Bank of Malta]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122163451/https://www.centralbankmalta.org/timeline-banknotes |archivedate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 December 2011, MaltaPost issued a [[miniature sheet]] containing a \u20ac4.16 stamp to commemorate the 90th anniversary of the establishment of Malta's [[Senate of Malta|Senate]] and [[Parliament of Malta|Legislative Assembly]]. This issue depicted the \u00a31 Melita stamp of 1922 as a [[stamp on stamp]].<ref name=\"maltapost2011\">{{cite news|title=Commemorative Stamp Issue \u2013 90th Anniversary of the Malta Senate and Legislative Assembly|url=https://www.maltaphilately.com/Content/Images/PDFs/Commemorative%20Stamp%20Issue.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316025224/https://www.maltaphilately.com/Content/Images/PDFs/Commemorative%20Stamp%20Issue.pdf|archivedate=16 March 2017|publisher=[[MaltaPost]]|date=1 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nCaruana Dingli's Melita design was reused for the [[Melita bullion coins]], a series of gold [[bullion coin]]s minted by the Central Bank of Malta in collaboration with [[Lombard Bank]]. The coins were minted in three sizes and denominations (\u20ac25, \u20ac50 and \u20ac100), and were first issued on 30 November 2018. There are plans to mint coins according to demand, retaining the same design except for the year of minting.<ref name=\"cbm-bullion\">{{cite web|title=Melita bullion coins 2018|url=https://www.centralbankmalta.org/en/2018-melita-bullion-coins|website=[[Central Bank of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121120928/https://www.centralbankmalta.org/en/2018-melita-bullion-coins|archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Postage stamps and postal history of Malta]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |title=Melita 1922\u201326 \u2013 Study Paper 24 |date=1972 |publisher=Malta Study Circle}}\n*{{cite magazine |last1=Pogson |first1=L. V. |title=Malta. 1922. \u00a31. |journal=Melita |volume=1 |issue=1 |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/site/userfiles/newsletter/01-01/173-45.pdf |publisher=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415130044/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/site/userfiles/newsletter/01-01/173-45.pdf |archivedate=15 April 2020}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category inline|Melita issue}}\n\n[[Category:Postage stamps]]\n[[Category:Commemorative stamps]]\n[[Category:Philately of Malta]]\n[[Category:1922 establishments in Malta]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple image|perrow = 3 |total_width=550\n| image1 = Malta 1922 Melita 1d orange & purple.jpg |width1=643|height1=779\n| image2 = Malta 1922 Melita 1s indigo & sepia.jpg |width2=643|height2=779\n| image3 = Malta 1922 Melita \u00a31 black & carmine-red.jpg |width3=643 |height3=779\n| footer = The different designs used in the Melita issue: [[Penny|pence]] values designed by [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] (left), [[shilling]] values by [[Gianni Vella]] (centre) and [[Pound sterling|pound]] value by Caruana Dingli{{efn|There are minor design differences between the pence and pound values which are both based on Caruana Dingli's design, including the shape of the value tablet and the typeface used for the country name.}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Melita issue''' is a series of dual-purpose [[Postage stamp|postage]]-and-[[Revenue stamp|revenue stamps]] issued by the [[Crown Colony of Malta]] between 1922 and 1926, depicting the national personification [[Melita (personification)|Melita]]. They were [[commemorative stamp]]s since they celebrated the islands' new status as a [[self-governing colony]] following a new constitution in 1921, but also a [[Definitive stamp|definitive issue]] intended for regular use over an extended period of time.\n\nDesigned by two leading Maltese artists, [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] and [[Gianni Vella]], the issue consisted of stamps in various denominations from \u00bc[[pence|d]] to [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]1; Caruana Dingli's designs were used on the pence and pound values and Vella's design on the shilling values. The designs were poorly received when they were issued, and Caruana Dingli himself criticized the execution of the design. In subsequent years, however, Caruana Dingli's design came to be regarded as one of the most iconic Malta stamps, and his design for the figure of Melita formed the basis of the [[Maltese lira]] banknotes of 1989\u20132008 and gold [[bullion coin]]s minted since 2018.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Malta 1899 Melita 2s6d olive-grey.jpg|thumb|left|The 1899 Melita stamp]]\n\nThe oldest known depiction of a personification of Malta dates back to 1481. The figure of [[Melita (personification)|Melita]] seems to have developed from allegorical representations of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St John]], which [[History of Malta under the Order of Saint John|ruled Malta]] between 1530 and 1798.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kinnane-Roelofsma |first1=Derk |title=Britannia and Melita: Pseudomorphic Sisters |journal=Journal of the Warbourg and Courtauld Insitute |date=1996 |volume=59 |pages=130\u2013147}}</ref>\n\nMelita first appeared on stamps in 1899. A 2[[shilling|s]]/6d olive-grey stamp depicted her holding a sword and a shield, the latter emblazoned with the [[Maltese cross]]. In the background were the flags of Malta and of the Order.<ref>{{cite web |title=The \"Melita\" Stamp of Malta |url=https://www.mintageworld.com/media/detail/7401-the-melita-stamp-of-malta/ |website=Mintage World |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122142635/https://www.mintageworld.com/media/detail/7401-the-melita-stamp-of-malta/ |archivedate=22 January 2019 |date=21 August 2018}}</ref> This stamp was reissued with a different [[watermark]] in 1919, and remained in use until it was replaced by the 1922 Melita issue.<ref name=\"sg\">{{cite book |title=Stanley Gibbons Stamp Catalogue: Commonwealth and British Empire Stamps 1840\u20131970 |date=2015 |publisher=[[Stanley Gibbons]] |location=London |isbn=978-0-85259-918-1 |pages=401\u2013402 |edition=117}}</ref> Special printings of the 1899 design, sometimes in new colours or watermarks, were also issued with [[overprint]]s for [[Revenue stamps of Malta|revenue purposes]] between 1902 and 1908.<ref name=\"mcclellan\"/>\n\nIn 1921, the British [[Crown Colony of Malta]] was granted a limited form of [[self-governing colony|self-government]] according to the Amery-Milner Constitution. This divided control of Malta between two governments: the Maltese Government and the Maltese Imperial Government. The former included a [[Bicameralism|bicameral legislature]] with a [[Senate of Malta|Senate]] and [[Parliament of Malta|Legislative Assembly]], while the Imperial Government was led by the [[List of Governors of Malta|Governor of Malta]], a British colonial official who retained direct responsibility of certain reserved matters such as defence and maintaining public order.<ref name=\"bephila\">{{cite web|title=Melita Issue of Malta Stamps: 1922\u201326|url=http://www.bephila.com/articles/melita-issue-of-malta-stamps-1922-26|website=British Empire Philately|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316113650/http://www.bephila.com/articles/melita-issue-of-malta-stamps-1922-26|archivedate=16 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Cassar |first1=Carmel |title=A Concise History of Malta |date=2000 |publisher=Mireva Publications |location=[[Msida]] |isbn=1870579526 |page=204}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June 1921, a [[design competition|competition]] was announced calling for the design of a set of stamps to commemorate Malta's partial independence. The stamps were therefore to be [[commemorative stamp|commemoratives]], but they were also intended as [[Definitive stamp|definitives]] for regular use over an extended period of time.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nThe Maltese wanted to issue the new stamps by the time the new parliament was inaugurated on 1 November 1921. There was not enough time for the stamps to be produced and delivered within that timeframe, however, since the printers [[De La Rue]] had to deal with a large workload, causing delays. The Malta Post Office therefore decided to overprint the then-current definitives (which depicted King [[George V]] and some pictorial scenes, including the 1919 reprint of the 1899 Melita design) with the words \"SELF-GOVERNMENT\" diagonally to commemorate the new constitution.<ref name=\"bephila\"/> The overprinting was carried out by the Government Printing Office in the capital [[Valletta]], and the stamps were released between 12 January and 29 April 1922.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\n==Design==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 320\n | image_style = border:none;\n | image1 = Malta -mix- 2019 by-RaBoe 260.jpg\n | alt1 = A lighthouse\n | image2 = Gozo boat cropped.jpg\n | alt2 = Painting of a boat\n | footer = The St Elmo lighthouse and a [[Gozo boat]] (painting pictured) are depicted in the background of Caruana Dingli's design\n}}\n\nTwo designs were chosen from the competition, one by [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] and one by [[Gianni Vella]]. Caruana Dingli's design was used for ten denominations: the [[Penny|pence]] values ranging from \u00bcd to 6d, and also the highest value of the set, the [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1. Vella's design was used for the five [[shilling]] values ranging from 1/- to 10/-.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nCaruana Dingli's design depicts [[Melita (personification)|Melita]] as a robed and helmeted figure holding a [[rudder]], representing Malta as being in control of her own destiny.<ref name=\"cbm-bullion\"/> The background contains a seascape, with the lighthouse near [[Fort Saint Elmo]] and a [[Gozo boat]] visible. Shields depicting the [[Union Jack]] and a colonial badge representing Malta are located at the bottom of the design.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nVella's design contains two figures representing Malta and the United Kingdom, Melita and [[Brittania]]. Melita holds an olive branch in her hand, and embraces Brittania by lifting her hand around Brittania's neck. Brittania wears a helmet and holds a shield with the Union Jack. The figure representing the United Kingdom is sometimes interpreted as being a male figure,<ref name=\"bephila\"/><ref name=\"times20111204\">{{cite news |last1=Bonavia |first1=Carmel |title=Stamps marking Malta's constitutional development |url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20111204/life-features/Stamps-marking-Malta-s-constitutional-development.397019 |work=[[Times of Malta]] |date=4 December 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911114312/https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20111204/life-features/Stamps-marking-Malta-s-constitutional-development.397019 |archivedate=11 September 2018}}</ref> but was intended as female, with the design representing Malta and Britain as sisters or mother and daughter.<ref name=\"linns\"/><ref name=\"bop1922\"/> This represented the care and protection that Britain offered Malta, and symbolized friendly relations between them. This design also contains the Roman numerals MCMXXI (1921) to the left of the figures. The Maltese emblem is located at the lower left corner, while many small Maltese crosses frame the design.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\n[[File:Malta 1922 Melita 1d orange &amp; purple postally and fiscally used.jpg|thumb|300px|Examples of the 1d orange and purple postally used (strip of three with [[Sliema]] postmarks) and fiscally used (single with an [[Anglo-Egyptian Bank]] cancellation)]]\n\nBoth designs contain the inscription \"POSTAGE [&] REVENUE\", indicating that they were valid for use as both [[postage stamp]]s and [[revenue stamp]]s. They can therefore be found both postally and fiscally used.<ref name=\"mcclellan\">{{cite web|last1=McClellan|first1=Andrew|title=Malta|url=http://www.revrevd.com/malta.html|website=Revenue Reverend|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924105952/http://www.revrevd.com/malta.html|archivedate=24 September 2017|date=2011\u201317}}</ref>\n\n==Technical details==\n[[File:Watermark crown script CA.jpg|thumb|left|The Multiple Script CA watermark]]\n\nThe stamps of the Melita issue were printed by De La Rue using typography, with the exception of the \u00a31 top value which was [[Intaglio (printmaking)|recess-printed]]. The typographed stamps were printed on chalk-surfaced paper. Each stamp was printed in two operations, with a [[Key type stamp|key plate and a duty plate]]. In most cases each plate was printed in a different colour, but for some of the low values both plates were printed in the same colour.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nThe [[watermark]] used on the stamps is known as ''Multiple Script CA'', since it consists of the letters \"CA\" (referring to the [[Crown Agents]]) in a script typeface, beneath a representation of the [[Tudor Crown (heraldry)|Tudor crown]], arranged multiple times next to each other. The watermark was sideways for the pence values and upright for the shilling values. The \u00a31 was initially printed with an upright watermark but in 1925 it was also issued with a sideways watermark.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nThe pence values were printed in sheets of 160 stamps (consisting of two panes, each containing 8 rows of 10 stamps, separated by a [[Gutter (philately)|gutter]]), the shilling values were printed in sheets of 80 (one pane of 8 rows of 10 stamps) and the \u00a31 value was printed in sheets of 40 (one pane of 4 rows of 10 stamps).<ref name=\"bephila\"/> The stamps were perforated with [[Perforation gauge|gauge]] 14.2 by 14 comb perforations.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nA number of [[Die proof (philately)|die proofs]] and plate proofs of stamps from the Melita issue exist. Die proofs are individual prints from the stamps' original [[Die (philately)|die]]s made at various stages of production, and are impressions of either the key die or the duty die of each value, or composite die proofs of both dies together. Plate proofs, which are test printings made from the stamps' printings plates, exist of the \u00bcd, \u00bdd, 1d, 3d and \u00a31 values in unissued colours. A wide range of versions of these exist, either perforated or imperforate, on unwatermarked or watermarked paper, and with or without a [[Specimen stamp|specimen overprint]]. Specimens of all the stamps in the issued colours also exist, except for the reprints made in slightly different shades, the 1925 2\u00bdd on 3d surcharge, and the 1926 postage overprints.<ref name=\"trory\"/>\n\n==Issued stamps==\n[[File:Malta 1925 Melita 2\u00bdd on 3d bright ultramarine.jpg|thumb|The 1925 2\u00bdd on 3d surcharge]]\n\nThe first Melita stamps were issued on 1 August 1922, with the denominations of \u00bdd, 1d, 6d, 1/- and 2/-. A \u00bcd value was issued on 22 August, followed by 2d, 3d, 4d, 2/6, 5/-, 10/- and \u00a31 values on 28 August. A 1\u00bdd value was added on 1 October 1923. On 25 April 1924, the 1d value was reissued in a new colour while the \u00bcd and 3d were reissued in slightly different shades.<ref name=\"jb\">{{cite book |last1=Buttigieg |first1=Joseph |title=The JB Catalogue of Malta Stamps and Postal History |date=2014 |publisher=Sliema Stamp Shop |location=[[Sliema]] |pages=10\u201311 |edition=22}}</ref> The \u00a31 was reissued in a slightly different shade and with a different orientation of the watermark on 14 May 1925.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\nA requirement for a 2\u00bdd value arose when the foreign-letter rate was reduced in 1925;<ref name=\"gps74\">{{cite journal |last1=Poulton |first1=Mark Anthony |title=The Gozo Boat on Malta Stamps |journal=Gozo Philatelic Society Newlsetter |date=2018 |issue=74 |pages=6\u201313 |url=https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar/handle/123456789/37744}}</ref> stocks of the 3d were overprinted \"Two pence halfpenny\" by the Government Printing Office and were issued on 3 December 1925. A 2\u00bdd value and the 3d in a new colour were subsequently issued on 16 February 1926.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Denomination\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" style =\"width:18%\" | Colour 1\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" style =\"width:18%\" | Colour 2\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" | Paper \n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" style =\"width:8%\" | Watermark orientation\n! scope=\"col\" | Date of issue\n|-\n| {{sort|000.25|\u00bcd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#773b31\" | brown || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-22|22 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|000.25|\u00bcd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#773b31\" | chocolate-brown || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1924-04-25|25 April 1924}}\n|- \n| {{sort|000.50|\u00bdd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#477159\" | green || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|001.00|1d}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#f67c36\" | orange || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#a33550\" | purple || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|001.00|1d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#894c78\" | bright violet || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1924-04-25|25 April 1924}}\n|- \n| {{sort|001.50|1\u00bdd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#a73422\" | brown-red || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1923-10-01|1 October 1923}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.00|2d}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#895732\" | bistre-brown || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#61beaa\" | turquoise || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.50|2\u00bdd on 3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#606fa8\" | cobalt || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1925-12-03|3 December 1925}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.50|2\u00bdd on 3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#476eb9\" | bright ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1925-12-09|9 December 1925}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.50|2\u00bdd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#476eb9\" | ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1926-02-16|16 February 1926}}\n|- \n| {{sort|003.00|3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#606fa8\" | cobalt || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|003.00|3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#476eb9\" | bright ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1924-04-25|25 April 1924}}\n|- \n| {{sort|003.00|3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#4a4742\" | black || bgcolor=\"#e6d649\" | yellow, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1926-02-16|16 February 1926}}\n|- \n| {{sort|004.00|4d}} || bgcolor=\"#febe2f\" | yellow || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#4c5b92\" | bright blue || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|006.00|6d}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#77743f\" | olive-green || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#5f3364\" | reddish violet || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|012.00|1/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#26486D\" | indigo || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#78462d\" | sepia || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|024.00|2/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#744028\" | brown || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#4c62a1\" | blue || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|030.00|2/6}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#9a427e\" | bright magenta || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#272528\" | black || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|060.00|5/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#c9672a\" | orange-yellow || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#384999\" | bright ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|120.00|10/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#837873\" | slate-grey || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#7c4d36\" | brown || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|240.00|\u00a31}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#211f22\" | black || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#b32026\" | carmine-red || white, ordinary || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|240.00|\u00a31}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#211f22\" | black || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#b32026\" | bright carmine || white, ordinary || sideways || {{sort|1925-05-14|14 May 1925}}\n|- \n|}\n\nSome stamps exist with an inverted watermark, and flaws are known on the 1d and 3d values.<ref name=\"trory\">{{cite book |title=The John A. Trory Specialised Catalogue of Malta |date=1990 |page=20 |edition=6}}</ref>\n\n==1926 Postage overprints==\n[[File:Malta 1926 Melita Postage 1\u00bdd brown-red.jpg|thumb|The 1\u00bdd with the \"POSTAGE\" overprint]]\n\nDue to a change in procedure, dual-purpose postage-and-revenue stamps were discontinued in 1926 and replaced by separate issues of postage stamps and revenue stamps,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Smeed|first1=Graham|title=Malta Revenue Stamps|date=1977|publisher=Malta Study Circle|page=5}}</ref> so it was decided to overprint the stamps of the Melita issue with the word \"POSTAGE\". The [[Forme (printing)|forme]] of the overprint was prepared by John Muscat Fenech and Carmelo Cacopardo, and the overprinting was hastily carried out by the Government Printing Office on a Warfedale printing press in the last week of March 1926. The ink used in the overprinting was a special mix made at the Office of Public Health.<ref name=\"invert\"/> The overprinting was applied to all the stamps from \u00bcd to 10/-, except those which had been earlier replaced by new colours, and the stamps were issued on 1 April 1926.<ref name=\"sg\"/> The overprints were on sale for only about a week, and a new series of stamps bearing the \"POSTAGE\" inscription was issued only five days later on 6 April.<ref name=\"sg\"/><ref name=\"gsm2019\">{{cite magazine |last1=Davenhill |first1=Noel |title=British Colonial and Protectorate Stamps \u2013 Part 19: Malta |magazine=[[Gibbons Stamp Monthly]] |date=December 2019 |volume=50 |issue=7 |pages=62\u201368 |publisher=Stanley Gibbons Ltd}}</ref>\n\nSome stamps with had errors were detected during the printing, and these were kept by the Acting Postmaster General before being burnt at the Power Station. Despite this, some stamps with errors still ended up in circulation, including the 3d value with the overprint inverted, and various denominations with the overprints misplaced to varying degrees, the most notable being a variety of the 4d in which the overprint reads \"AGE POST\".<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\n===3d with inverted overprint===\n[[File:Malta 1926 Melita Postage 3d black on yellow overprint inverted.jpg|thumb|The 3d with the \"POSTAGE\" overprint inverted]]\n\nThe 3d black on yellow is known with the [[Invert error|overprint inverted]], and it is one of Malta's best-known error stamps. It is believed that only two sheets of the error were printed, and they were allegedly acquired on the first day of issue by Alfredo Caruana Gatto, a [[Maltese Political Union]] politician who was a member of the Senate and who had been Minister for Justice in 1921\u201322. The exact circumstances of their issue remain unclear, and it is not known whether they were acquired over the Post Office counter or not. Caruana Gatto is said to have immediately sold the two sheets to Carol Saliba and Pio Grech, and the sheets were eventually broken down and sold to stamp dealers and collectors. A small amount of the error stamps were used on mail by philatelists, but the vast majority were retained in [[Mint stamp|mint condition]].<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\nIn 1930, uncertainty about the stamp's issue formed the basis of a political campaign by the [[Constitutional Party (Malta)|Constitutional Party]] against the [[Nationalist Party (Malta)|Nationalist Party]] which became known as the \"Postage Stamps Scandal\". The matter was brought up in the Legislative Assembly on 31 March 1930 when Constitutional Party member Alfred Gera De Petri asked Robert Hamilton, the Minister for Posts, about the circumstances of the stamp's issue. A committee was later appointed to investigate the matter, and it included [[Gerald Strickland, 1st Baron Strickland|Gerald Strickland]], Hamilton, Walter Salomone, [[Paul Boffa]] and [[Ugo Pasquale Mifsud]].<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\nThe committee members belonging to the Constitutional Party produced a report in which they stated that there was no evidence that the error was ever sold at a Post Office or that Caruana Gatto (who had died in 1926) had sold the stamps. They concluded that the inverted overprint was applied at the Government Printing Office without authorisation to sheets of genuine stamps which were not part of the Post Office stock, meaning that the overprints were forged. Boffa mentioned that the overprinting might have even been done outside the Government Printing Office, while Mifsud only agreed with the conclusion that there was no evidence of Caruana Gatto's involvement in the matter. There were gaps in the evidence collected by the committee, and it did not produce any arguments which countered various opinions that the overprints were the result of a genuine mistake, making its findings inconclusive. The committee's report was criticized in the press.<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\nPhilatelists regard the inverted overprint as a genuine error,<ref name=\"sg\"/> even though its exact origins remain unknown.<ref name=\"invert\">{{cite journal |last1=Ganado |first1=Albert |title=The Melita 3d. Postage Inverted: Politics embroil philately |journal=Melita Historica |date=2007 |volume=XIV |issue=4 |pages=409\u2013428 |url=http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Melita%20Historica/MH.14(2004-07)/MH.14(2007)4/04.pdf |issn=1021-6952|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121232400/http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Melita%20Historica/MH.14(2004-07)/MH.14(2007)4/04.pdf|archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe stamps received mostly negative reactions from the public and stamp collectors upon their release. Even Caruana Dingli was dissatisfied with the way the stamps were printed, stating in the local newspaper ''Il Popolo di Malta'' on 4 August 1922 that:<ref name=\"times20111204\"/>\n{{cquote|After correcting the first proofs and suggesting certain artistic retouching, I regret to say, that the result still fell short of my expectations. My original was copied by hand and alterations were introduced resulting in a totally different effect from that originally intended.|20px}}\nAmongst other criticism, he expressed his dissatisfaction that the lighthouse in the background was remodelled to look like a [[beehive]] or the [[Rotunda of Mosta|Mosta Dome]]. He also complained that the colours were not to his liking, and that he had not been consulted about them. He exhibited an enlarged version of his original design at the [[National Library of Malta|Bibliotheca]] in Valletta to showcase the difference in the designs.<ref name=\"times20111204\"/>\n\n[[File:Malta 1922 Melita 4d yellow &amp; bright blue.jpg|thumb|left|The colour scheme of the 4d was criticized when the stamps were issued]]\n\nAn article in ''[[The Boy's Own Paper]]'' described the issue as a \"handsome set\", but also mentioned the criticism aimed at the colour scheme of the 4d value in yellow and blue. This article incorrectly identified Melita as being a [[Nereid|sea nymph]].<ref name=\"bop1922\">{{cite book |title=The Boy's Own Paper |date=1922 |publisher=Leisure Hour Office |pages=227\u2013228 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IsPnAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA227#v=onepage&q&f=false |volume=45 |chapter=The \"B.O.P.\" Stamp Corner}}</ref> In ''Mekeel's Weekly Stamp News'' of 16 May 1927, a certain Capt. H. W. Jessop wrote that:<ref name=\"linns\">{{cite web |title=Malta's 1922 Melita issue: Fine art or poorly done stamps? |url=https://www.linns.com/news/us-stamps-postal-history/2017/january/malta-melita-stamp-issue-fine-art-poorly-done.html |website=[[Linn's Stamp News]] |date=1 January 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/75cWftBrr|archivedate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n{{cquote|though not in themselves displeasing, [the stamps] did not meet with a very enthusiastic reception either from the general public or from collectors.|20px}}\nCriticism was also directed towards the lack of a portrait of King [[George V]] on the stamps, although the stamps were aimed at specifically manifesting Malta's newly established freedom from total British control.<ref name=\"linns\"/>\n\nThe 1926 Postage overprints were widely criticized as being unnecessary,<ref name=\"gsm2019\"/> and they were unpopular both locally and among collectors.<ref name=\"gps74\"/>\n\nIn contrast to when it was issued, today Caruana Dingli's design is held in high esteem, and in 2011 [[MaltaPost]] stated that \"it is widely considered to be one of Malta's most beautiful stamps.\"<ref name=\"maltapost2011\"/> A 2019 article in the ''Stamp Magazine'' describes the Melita issue as \"some of Malta's finest\" stamp designs, but also comments on the contrast between Caruana Dingli's and Vella's Melitas, describing the latter as having \"an awkward pose\".<ref name=\"stampmagazine2019\">{{cite magazine |last1=Winchester |first1=John |title=The odd couple |magazine=Stamp Magazine |date=February 2019 |volume=85 |issue=2 |page=51}}</ref>\n\n==Sale and collecting==\nIn 1922\u201323 the Post Office recorded an increase of \u00a31920. 19s. 9\u00bdd. in revenue when compared to the previous year.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1922 |date=1923 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108153623/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref> This increase was attributed to the sale of stamps to [[philately|philatelists]] \"owing to the issue of new design stamps\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1924 |date=1925 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1924/1924_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108154434/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1924/1924_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref>{{efn|The statistics in the 1922 Blue Book are for the period lasting from 1 April 1922 to 31 March 1923.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1922 |date=1923 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section2.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108153618/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section2.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Abstract of the Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref> The only new stamps issued during this period were a \u00bcd surcharged stamp on 15 April, 6d and \u00bdd Self-Government overprints on 19 and 24 April respectively, and the Melita issue between 1 and 28 August. The Melita issue was the only issue with a new design.<ref name=\"sg\"/>}} A massive increase of \u00a327977. 16s. 6\u00bdd.  in Post Office revenue was registered in 1925\u201326 when compared to 1924\u201325, and this was attributed to \"an abnormal quantity of stamps sold to collectors for philatelic purposes\" along with increased use of stamps for postal purposes.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1926 |date=1927 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108155457/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref>{{efn|The statistics in the 1926 Blue Book are for the period lasting from 1 April 1925 to 31 March 1926.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1926 |date=1927 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section2.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108155453/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section2.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Abstract of the Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref> The only new postage stamps issued during this period were all from the Melita issue: the reprint of the \u00a31 on 14 May 1925, the 2\u00bdd on 3d surcharge in December 1925, and the 2\u00bdd and 3d in new colours on 16 February 1926. In addition, there were two new sets of [[postage due]] stamps issued on 16 April and 20 July 1925.<ref name=\"sg\"/>}} In 1926\u201327, another massive increase of \u00a324870. 8s. 2d. was attributed to \"large sales of stamps overprinted \"Postage\".\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1927 |date=1928 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1927/1927_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108160038/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1927/1927_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref>\n\nDue to the criticism at the colour scheme of the 4d value, that stamp was reportedly withdrawn by the postal authorities soon after it was issued. Some believed that the stamp could become a rarity and examples of it were sold for as much as 30/-. After a couple of days the stamp once again became available at post offices,<ref name=\"bop1922\"/> and it is no longer scarcer than the other stamps in the issue.<ref name=\"sg\"/> Today, the 1922\u201326 stamps are not rare, and the lower values up to the 2/6 are relatively cheap. The higher values are more expensive,<ref name=\"stampmagazine2019\"/> with the most valuable stamp being the original \u00a31 value of 1922 with a sideways watermark.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\n[[File:Malta 1930 AR cover to United States.jpg|thumb|1\u00bdd and 3d Melita stamps with the \"POSTAGE\" overprint used on a 1930 registered cover to the United States. The cover was sent by Rupert Forbes-Bentley, a stamp dealer.<ref name=\"invert\"/>]]\n\nAlthough the 1926 Postage overprints were only on sale for about one week, the bulk of the stamps were sold to stamp dealers and collectors so most of them remain common. However, some values sold out soon after they were issued<ref name=\"gps74\"/> and stamps with the denominations of 4d, 2/-, 2/6 and 5/- are quite expensive today. Since they were only in use briefly, most of the 1926 overprints are more valuable in used condition.<ref name=\"sg\"/> The \"POSTAGE\" overprint has also been [[Philatelic fakes and forgeries|forged]], particularly on the 2/- and 2/6 denominations and on the 3d with inverted overprint.<ref name=\"trory\"/>\n\nThe Malta Study Circle, a group of philatelists who study Malta's stamps and postal history, has produced a number of publications relating to the Melita issue. Two study papers which related to the original 1922\u201326 issue and the 1926 Postage overprints were published in 1970,<ref>{{cite web |title=Melita 1922\u20131926 |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?revHistory=24&category=0 |website=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415112251/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?revHistory=24&category=0 |archivedate=15 April 2020}}</ref> and they were combined into a single paper in 1972. A rewritten paper was published in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=Study Papers |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?pageInfo=2&thisPageSize=20 |website=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415112254/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?pageInfo=2&thisPageSize=20 |archivedate=15 April 2020}}</ref> The Study Circle's newsletter which is published three times a year is also entitled ''Melita''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/about/information.asp |website=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415112257/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/about/information.asp |archivedate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nAn allegorical figure with a pose similar to Caruana Dingli's Melita design was used on the fifth and final series of [[Maltese lira]] banknotes. These banknotes were introduced by the [[Central Bank of Malta]] on 18 September 1989, coinciding with the 25th anniversary of independence, and they had four denominations: Lm2, Lm5, Lm10 and Lm20. Another series of banknotes with the same design but with amended security features was issued on 1 June 1994. Versions with signatures of different Governors of the Central Bank were issued in 1997, 1999 and 2001, and there was also a special issue for collectors in 2000.<ref>{{cite book |title=Said Malta Coin & Banknote Catalogue 2010 |date=2010 |publisher=Said International Ltd |pages=180\u2013193}}</ref> These banknotes remained in use until Malta adopted the [[euro]] on 1 January 2008, and remained legal tender until 31 January 2008; they were demonetized ten years later on 31 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maltese banknotes \u2013 5th Series and enhanced version (not legal tender after 31 January 2008)|url=http://www.centralbankmalta.org/site/currency2e.html|publisher=[[Central Bank of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227162525/http://www.centralbankmalta.org/site/currency2e.html|archivedate=27 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Timeline Banknotes |url=https://www.centralbankmalta.org/timeline-banknotes |website=[[Central Bank of Malta]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122163451/https://www.centralbankmalta.org/timeline-banknotes |archivedate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 December 2011, MaltaPost issued a [[miniature sheet]] containing a \u20ac4.16 stamp to commemorate the 90th anniversary of the establishment of Malta's [[Senate of Malta|Senate]] and [[Parliament of Malta|Legislative Assembly]]. This issue depicted the \u00a31 Melita stamp of 1922 as a [[stamp on stamp]].<ref name=\"maltapost2011\">{{cite news|title=Commemorative Stamp Issue \u2013 90th Anniversary of the Malta Senate and Legislative Assembly|url=https://www.maltaphilately.com/Content/Images/PDFs/Commemorative%20Stamp%20Issue.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316025224/https://www.maltaphilately.com/Content/Images/PDFs/Commemorative%20Stamp%20Issue.pdf|archivedate=16 March 2017|publisher=[[MaltaPost]]|date=1 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nCaruana Dingli's Melita design was reused for the [[Melita bullion coins]], a series of gold [[bullion coin]]s minted by the Central Bank of Malta in collaboration with [[Lombard Bank]]. The coins were minted in three sizes and denominations (\u20ac25, \u20ac50 and \u20ac100), and were first issued on 30 November 2018. There are plans to mint coins according to demand, retaining the same design except for the year of minting.<ref name=\"cbm-bullion\">{{cite web|title=Melita bullion coins 2018|url=https://www.centralbankmalta.org/en/2018-melita-bullion-coins|website=[[Central Bank of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121120928/https://www.centralbankmalta.org/en/2018-melita-bullion-coins|archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Postage stamps and postal history of Malta]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |title=Melita 1922\u201326 \u2013 Study Paper 24 |date=1972 |publisher=Malta Study Circle}}\n*{{cite magazine |last1=Pogson |first1=L. V. |title=Malta. 1922. \u00a31. |journal=Melita |volume=1 |issue=1 |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/site/userfiles/newsletter/01-01/173-45.pdf |publisher=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415130044/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/site/userfiles/newsletter/01-01/173-45.pdf |archivedate=15 April 2020}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category inline|Melita issue}}\n\n[[Category:Postage stamps]]\n[[Category:Commemorative stamps]]\n[[Category:Philately of Malta]]\n[[Category:1922 establishments in Malta]]\n", "name_user": "Xwejnusgozo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melita_issue"}
