sassination]] of his mother, [[Indira Gandhi|Prime Minister Indra Gandhi]]. He was the longest serving Gen. Secretary of All India National Congress (1980 - 1988), and served with [[Indira Gandhi|Prime Minister Indra Gandhi]], [[Sanjay Gandhi]] and [[Rajiv Gandhi|Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi]].\n*[[Dick Morris]] \u2013 orchestrated the gubernatorial and presidential elections of [[Bill Clinton]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Over-50 |url=http://over-50.typepad.com/over-50/2010/09/dick-morris-kingmaker.html |title=Dick Morris: Kingmaker - Over-50 |publisher=Over-50.typepad.com |date=2010-09-25 |accessdate=2012-04-14}}</ref>\n*[[Girija Prasad Koirala]] \u2013 described as a kingmaker in [[Nepal]] with the election of [[Madhav Kumar Nepal]]<ref>[http://www.zeenews.com/news534020.html Zee news]</ref>\n*[[Fred Malek]] \u2013 described as a kingmaker for the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] in the United States<ref>[http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0509/22736.html Politico]</ref>\n*[[David Axelrod (political consultant)|David Axelrod]] \u2013 described by ''[[U.S. News and World Report]]'' as a \"reporter turned kingmaker\" with respect to the ascendancy of [[Barack Obama]]<ref>\n\"[https://www.usnews.com/articles/news/obama/2009/05/19/obamas-power-players-axelrod-helps-refine-the-presidents-message.html Obama's Power Players: Axelrod Helps Refine the President's Message]\", ''U.S. News & World Report'', 19 May 2009.</ref>\n*[[Bakili Muluzi]] \u2013 described as a kingmaker in [[Malawi]]<ref>[http://www.nyasatimes.com/national/3424.html ''Nyasa Times''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515133533/http://www.nyasatimes.com/national/3424.html |date=2009-05-15 }}</ref>\n*[[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]] \u2013 an influential politician who became an ideological leader of [[All-India Muslim League]] and the first [[Governor-General]] of [[Pakistan]]; widely regarded as the founder of [[Pakistan]].\n*[[Stefan Cardinal Wyszy\u0144ski]] \u2013 was highly instrumental in the [[October 1978 papal conclave|1978 papal election]] of [[Karol Wojty\u0142a]], [[Archbishop of Krak\u00f3w]], as [[John Paul&nbsp;II]]\n*[[Rupert Murdoch]] \u2013 a media tycoon in ownership of [[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp]] and the [[Fox Corporation]] who has consistently backed every winning [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] since the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 general election]].\n*[[Nick Clegg]] \u2013 described as a kingmaker in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 UK general election]] as the leader of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] following a [[hung parliament]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8440502.stm |title=Nick Clegg 'will not be a post-election king-maker' |publisher=BBC News |date=2010-01-05 |accessdate=2012-04-14}}</ref>\n*[[Richard J. Daley]] as [[Mayor of Chicago]] and Chairman of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] of [[Cook County]] was the leading figure in the [[Democratic Party of Illinois|Illinois Democratic Party]]. As such, he controlled a large bloc of delegates at [[Democratic National Convention]]s and provided crucial support to Democratic Presidential nominees, including [[Adlai Stevenson II|Adlai Stevenson]], [[John F. Kennedy]], [[Lyndon Johnson]], and [[Hubert Humphrey]].<ref>{{cite web|title=RICHARD J. DALEY: KINGMAKER BOOK CHRONICLES DALEY'S IRON GRIP ON CHICAGO|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-63177527.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924161635/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-63177527.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 September 2015|website=highbeam.com|publisher=The Wisconsin State Journal|date=2 July 2000|accessdate=10 May 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Central Europe|Central European]] politicians, including Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] of [[Germany]] (2000\u2013present)  and Prime Minister [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]] of [[Hungary]] (1998\u2013present){{explain|date=February 2018}}\n*[[Kurds]] in Middle East especially in [[Southern Kurdistan]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The Middle East's Newest Kingmakers|url=http://www.vocativ.com/world/iraq-world/middle-easts-newest-kingmakers/|quote=the Kurds in Iraq, Syria and Turkey now have a chance to become the Middle East's most unlikely power brokers|website=vocativ.com|accessdate=10 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605103949/http://www.vocativ.com/world/iraq-world/middle-easts-newest-kingmakers/|archive-date=5 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Jaros\u0142aw Kaczy\u0144ski]], [[Poland]]'s kingmaker according to ''[[Financial Times|The Financial Times]]'' on February 2016.\n*[[Democratic Unionist Party]] and its leader [[Arlene Foster]] became regarded as a kingmaker after the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|June 2017 general election]] resulted in a hung parliament.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arlene Foster: DUP leader emerges as the kingmaker, but who is she?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/09/dup-leader-arlene-foster-emerges-kingmaker/}}</ref>\n*[[Winston Peters]], [[New Zealand|New Zealand']]<nowiki/>s kingmaker after both the [[New Zealand general election, 1996|1996]] and [[New Zealand general election, 2017|2017]] elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11925764}}</ref>\n*[[Avigdor Lieberman]] and his party [[Yisrael Beiteinu]] in the [[September 2019 Israeli legislative election]].\n\n==In game theory==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2017}}\n{{main|Kingmaker scenario}}\n\nIn [[game theory]], a kingmaker is a player who lacks sufficient resources or position to win at a given game, but possesses enough remaining resources to decide which of the remaining viable players will eventually win.\n\n==Contemporary usage==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2016}}\nThe term \"kingmaker\", though always unofficial, has tended to gain more importance in places of power struggle\u2014e.g., politics, sports organizations etc. Consequently, bestowal of such a title is looked upon significantly and more often as a means of indirect gratification for individuals wanting to silently dictate the affairs of the organization. The term is also occasionally used in a pejorative sense during elections where a small number of independent political candidate(s) who hold a sizeable sway in the \"vote bank\" can most likely decide the course of an outcome.\n\nAs well as referring to an individual, the term can also be applied to institutions or think tanks whose opinions are held in great regard by the interested organization. The influence of the religious orders like the Roman Catholic Church in running the affairs of the state during medieval times (through the king) is a well-known example. Kingdoms and empires in the Indian sub-continent often relied on their religious heads. Besides religious orders, even countries can fit into this terminology when they can dictate the affairs of the other country (either directly or indirectly). In current political scenarios across the world the term can expand its scope to include powerful [[lobbying]] groups, whose role is often seen as a defining factor on major issues.\n\nCitizens of [[West Africa]]n sub-national monarchies often use the word ''kingmaker'' to refer to the members of the electoral colleges that choose their sovereigns because they also usually officiate during the coronation rituals and rites of purification, the word in this particular case taking on a literal meaning i.e. a ''maker'' of the king.\n\nThe term \"kingmaker\" is also used to describe situations in multi-player games where a player is either unable to win or has claimed an unassailable lead, but, in either case, plays a strong role in determining the outcome for other players.\n\n==In fiction==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2017}}\n* The character [[Leon Fortunato]] from the ''[[Left Behind (series)|Left Behind]]'' series of novels is often described as a kingmaker.\n* Marcus Jefferson Wall, the antagonist of much of the [[Matador series]] by Steve Perry is called the Kingmaker, and controls the President of the Galactic Federation\n* The character [[Mayvar|Mayvar Kingmaker]] from the ''[[Saga of the Exiles]]'' series of novels tests the ability of aspirants before they can be proclaimed king of the [[Saga of Pliocene Exile#Tanu and Firvulag|Tanu]].\n* Ser Criston Cole, a character from [[George R.&nbsp;R. Martin]]\u2019s ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'' series, is commonly referred to as \"the kingmaker\".\n* Minato Yoko, a character from [[Kamen Rider Gaim]], considers herself a kingmaker, wanting to see who has what it takes to take the Forbidden Fruit, a fruit of great power that can essentially make a person a king. Likewise, another character, Mitsuzane Kureshima, also has traits of a kingmaker, hanging around with and manipulating events so as to put the ruler in his favor.\n* Harry Leong, the ultra-rich, secretive billionaire from ''[[Crazy Rich Asians]]'', is revealed to be one of the kingmakers in the government of Singapore.\n* One of the villains in the NBC TV series ''[[The Blacklist (TV series)|The Blacklist]]'' went under the alias ''The Kingmaker''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Political terminology]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kingmaker"}
